lm\n|-\n|2019\n|Isn't It Romantic presents A Real Housewives\u2019 Rom-Com<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/Bttuh3ohMW8/|title=Real Housewives Beverly Hills on Instagram: \"\ud83d\udc98 \u2018Isn\u2019t It Romantic\u2019 presents A Real Housewives\u2019 Rom-Com @theprettymess @kylerichards18 @doritkemsley \ud83d\udc8e #RHOBH \ud83d\udc96\ud83d\udd25\ud83d\udc40\ud83e\udd42\ud83d\udc8b #realhousewives\u2026\"|website=Instagram|language=en|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref>\n|Bravo\n|Short film promoting the film ''[[Isn't It Romantic (2019 film)|Isn't It Romantic]]''\n|-Herself\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Theatre\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Chicago (musical)|Chicago]]''\n|[[Roxie Hart]]\n|[[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]\n|}\n\n== Concerts ==\n=== Tours ===\n<ul><li>[[Erika Jayne Presents: The Pretty Mess Tour|The Pretty Mess Tour]] (2018)</li></ul>\n\n==Published works==\n* Jayne, Erika. ''Pretty Mess.'' New York: Gallery Books, 2018. {{ISBN|1501181890}}.\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2015\n| LGBT Ally Awards\n| News Ally Entertainer<ref>{{cite web|last1=Senzee|first1=Thom|title=Allred, Jayne to Receive LGBT Ally \u2018Elgy\u2019 Awards Thursday Night in L.A.-Public Invited|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/thom-senzee/allred-jayne-to-receive-l_b_6509358.html|website=The Huffington Post|accessdate=October 13, 2016|date=January 21, 2015}}</ref>\n| \n| {{won}}\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Accolades ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Publisher\n!Country\n!Accolade\n!Rank\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|100 Greatest of All Time Top Dance Club Artists<ref name=\":16\" />\n|align=\"center\"|42\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''\n|[[United States]]\n|Next Big Sound<ref name=\":12\" />\n|align=\"center\"|3\n|-\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of number-one dance hits (United States)]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the U.S. Dance chart]]\n* [[List of number one dance airplay hits (United States)]]\n* [[List of artists who reached number one on the U.S. dance airplay chart]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.erikajayne.com/ Official website]\n*{{IMDb name|nm0149633}}\n*{{IBDB name|524341}}\n\n{{Erika Jayne}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jayne, Erika}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American dance musicians]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Atlanta]]\n[[Category:The Real Housewives cast members]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women singers]]\n", "name_user": "Kahtar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Repair CS1 error(s), replaced: website=www. \u2192 website=", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Erika_Jayne"}
{"title_page": "Papa John's Pizza", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Papa John\u2019s Pizza, Inc.\n| trading_name =\n| logo = Papa John's Logo 2019.svg\n| image = Papa johns.jpg\n| image_caption = A Papa John's in [[Front Royal, Virginia]]\n| type = [[Public Company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{NASDAQ|PZZA}}<br />[[S&P 400|S&P 400 Component]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1984|10|02}}\n| location = [[Jeffersontown, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| num_locations = 5,395<br />(December 2019)<ref name=10K/>\n| founder = [[John Schnatter]]\n| key_people = Rob Lynch <br />{{small|(President and CEO)}}<br />Karlin Linhardt<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ir.papajohns.com/corporate-governance/management|date= Aug 27, 2019|title=Papa John's names new global chief marketing officer|work=[[Nation's Restaurant News]]|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref><br />{{small|[[Chief marketing officer|CMO]]}}\n| industry = Pizza, Pizza Delivery\n| revenue = {{Decrease}} US$1.619 billion {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K>{{cite report |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/901491/000155837020001393/pzza-20191229x10kcbc0c2.htm|title=Papa John's International, Inc. Form 10-K for 2019 |website=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| products = [[Pizza]], [[Chicken as food|chicken wings]], [[dessert]]\n| operating_income = {{Decrease}} US$24.535 million {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| net_income = {{Increase}} US$4.866 million {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| assets = {{Increase}} US$730.721 million {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| equity = {{Decrease}} -US$316.656 million {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| num_employees = ~16,500 {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| homepage = {{url|papajohns.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Papa John's''' is an American [[pizza]] restaurant franchise. It's the fourth largest [[pizza delivery]] [[Chain store#Restaurant chains|restaurant chain]] in the United States,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pmq.com/December-2014/Pizza-PowerThe-2015-Pizza-Power-Report/ |title=The 2015 Pizza Power Report |last=Hynum |first=Rick |date=2014 |website=Pizza Magazine |publisher=PMQ |access-date=26 October 2018 |quote= }}</ref> with headquarters in [[Jeffersontown, Kentucky]], a suburb of [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Papa John's Pizza logo.svg|thumb|Previous logo]]\nThe Papa John's restaurant was founded in 1984 when \"Papa\" [[John Schnatter]] knocked out a broom closet in the back of his father's tavern, Mick's Lounge, in [[Jeffersonville, Indiana]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolfson|first1=Andrew|title=The real Papa John: Pizza entrepreneur John Schnatter makes no apologies for wealth, success, Obamacare remarks {{!}} Math whiz mixed pizza passion, finance |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/money/2013/01/13/the-real-papa-john-pizza-entrepreneur-john-schnatter-m/28936389/ |accessdate=March 22, 2017|work=[[The Courier-Journal]]|date=January 13, 2013}}</ref> He then sold his [[Chevrolet Camaro (second generation)|1971 Camaro Z28]] to purchase [[US$]]1,600 worth of used pizza equipment and began selling pizzas to the tavern's customers out of the converted closet.<ref name=\"PJStory\" /> His pizzas proved sufficiently popular that a year later he moved into an adjoining space. Dipping sauce specifically for pizza was invented by Papa John's Pizza that same year, and has since become popular when eating pizza, especially the crust.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shrikant|first1=Adit|title=How Dipping Sauce for Pizza Became Oddly Necessary |url=https://www.eater.com/2017/7/27/16021832/pizza-dipping-sauce-papa-johns-garlic-dominos-sauce|website=Eater|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> The company went public in 1993. A year later it had 500 stores, and by 1997 it had opened 1,500 stores.<ref>{{cite web|title=This Marketing Insight Made Papa John's A Household Name|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/papa-johns-marketing-insight-2014-5?IR=T/|website=Business Insider|date=May 21, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> In 2009, Schnatter reacquired the Camaro back after offering a reward of $250,000 for the car.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Found: Papa John's Long-Lost Camaro! Kentucky Man Receives $250,000 Finder's Fee |date=August 25, 2009 |publisher=Papa John's |url=http://ir.papajohns.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=404954 |accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''PMQ Pizza Magazine'' said in December 2016 that the company was the third-largest take-out and pizza delivery restaurant chain in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza Power 2017 \u2013 A State of the Industry Report|url=http://www.pmq.com/December-2016/Pizza-Power-2017-A-State-of-the-Industry-Report/|website=PMQ Pizza Magazine|date=December 2016|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref> (According to PMQ, [[Little Caesars]] is the third-largest pizza chain; however, it does not deliver.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/05/31/why-little-caesars-doesnt-need-delivery-to-compete-in-the-restaurant-industry.html |title=This is why Little Caesars won't be investing in delivery |newspaper=Cnbc.com |date=May 31, 2017|author=Sarah Whitten|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref>) The company's net profitability though, is far behind its main competitors. In 2014 its net margin was 4.6% of total sales, whereas [[Domino's Pizza]]'s net margin was 8.2% and [[Yum! Brands]], which owns [[Pizza Hut]], was 7.9%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://marketrealist.com/2015/12/comparing-papa-johns-net-margins-quick-service-big-guns |title=Papa John's Marketing and Promotional Strategies: What's in the Oven? |newspaper=Market Realist |date=December 10, 2015|author=Ralph Nathan|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> Company headquarters are in Jeffersontown, Kentucky, a community within the [[Louisville Metro Council|merged government]] of Louisville.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/doc/241428416.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov%2007,%202007&author=&pub=Courier%20-%20Journal&edition=&startpage=&desc=Jeffersontown%20to%20dedicate%20new%20bike%20and%20walking%20path%20Saturday |title=Jeffersontown to dedicate new bike and walking path Saturday |newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=November 7, 2007 |page=C7 |accessdate=December 6, 2012 |quote=Papa John's office is in Jeffersontown |url-access=subscription  |first=Chris |last=Otts |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326131049/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/doc/241428416.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov%2007,%202007&author=&pub=Courier%20-%20Journal&edition=&startpage=&desc=Jeffersontown%20to%20dedicate%20new%20bike%20and%20walking%20path%20Saturday |archive-date=March 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.papajohns.com/pizzachallenge/index.shtm |title=Papa's Specialty Pizza Challenge |website=Papa John's Pizza |accessdate=December 6, 2012 |quote=Papa John's International Inc., 2002 Papa John's Blvd, Louisville, KY 40299 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801210325/http://www.papajohns.com/pizzachallenge/index.shtm |archive-date=August 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |author=<!--not specified-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite map |url=http://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/GUBlock/st21_ky/place/p2140222_jeffersontown/DC10BLK_P2140222_001.pdf |title=2010 Census \u2013 Census Block Map (Index): Jeffersontown city, KY |publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]] |date=2010 |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref> Its slogan is \"Better Ingredients. Better Pizza. Papa John's.\"\n\nPapa John's has over 5,199 establishments\u20144,456 franchised restaurants operating domestically in all 50 states and in 44 countries and territories. Papa John's operates 246 \"company owned stores\" under joint ventures and 35 units in Beijing and North China.<ref name=10K/> In September 2012 the 4,000th Papa John's Pizza restaurant opened, in [[New Hyde Park, New York]]. The company celebrated the event by giving away 4,000 free pizzas to customers throughout New York City.<ref name=\"PJStory\">{{cite web |url=http://www.papajohns.co.uk/our-story/history.aspx |title=The Papa John's Story |publisher=Papa John's (GB) Ltd |accessdate=August 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710004930/http://www.papajohns.co.uk/our-story/history.aspx |archive-date=July 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://ir.papajohns.com/releaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=706740 |title=Papa John's Celebrates Opening of 4,000th Restaurant Worldwide |accessdate=September 16, 2012 |date=September 13, 2012 |website=Papa John's International, Inc.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/franchises/papajohnsintlinc/282662 |title=Papa John's Int'l. Inc. Franchise Information |magazine=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]] |accessdate=September 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe company announced on December 21, 2017, that John Schnatter would step down as CEO of Papa John's Pizza on January 1, 2018, to be replaced as CEO by current company President [[Steve Ritchie (businessman)|Steve Ritchie]] with Schnatter remaining chairman at the time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/12/21/papa-johns-ceo-john-schnatter-steps-down/974917001/ |title=Papa John's CEO, pizza titan John Schnatter, steps down |accessdate=December 21, 2017 |date=December 21, 2017 |author=Zlati Meyer}}</ref> In February 2018, Papa John's and the NFL mutually agreed to end their sponsorship agreement after Schnatter's criticism of the NFL made headlines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2018/02/27/papa-johns-nfl-end-sponsorship-agreement-after-anthem-protest-controversy/|title=Pizza Hut scores NFL pizza sponsorship deal after Papa John's bows out|last=Boren|first=Cindy |date=February 28, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 1, 2018|last2=Flaherty|first2=Bryan|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nOn July 11, 2018, news outlets reported that during a conference call with Papa Johns' marketing agency Laundry Services, Schnatter had used the word \"nigger\" by saying \"[[Colonel Sanders]] called blacks niggers and Sanders never faced public backlash.\" Schnatter alleged that referencing the quote by the [[KFC]] founder was meant to convey his dislike for racism.<ref>{{cite news|first=Noah|last=Kirsch |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/noahkirsch/2018/07/11/papa-johns-founder-john-schnatter-allegedly-used-n-word-on-conference-call/ |title=Papa John's Founder Used N-Word On Conference Call|work=[[Forbes]]|publisher=[[Forbes Media]]|location=New York City|date=July 11, 2018}}</ref> After the call, the owner of the marketing agency moved to end their contract with Papa John's. Schnatter resigned as chairman of the board on the same day the incident was reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/07/11/news/companies/papa-johns-pizza-john-schnatter/index.html|title=Papa John's founder resigns as chairman after using N-word on conference call|first=Nathaniel|last=Meyersohn|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the incident, Ritchie apologized in an open letter and ordered the company's workforce to undergo bias and diversity training.<ref>{{citation|title=Papa John's orders workers to undergo bias and diversity training|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/nation-now/2018/08/24/papa-johns-bias-diversity-training/1085908002/}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Papa John's CEO Attempts Damage Control But Not An Apology|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/papa-johns-damage-control_n_5b49237de4b0bc69a78749ea}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2018, [[John Schnatter]] filed a [[lawsuit]] against Papa John's Pizza to give him access to the company's [[financial statements|books]] and records after they fired him from the company after the teleconference call scandal. He describes the company's procedures as an \"unexplained and heavy-handed way\" to cut ties between him and the company that he founded. In addition to preventing him from accessing information, the corporation has also implemented a [[Shareholder rights plan|poison pill strategy]] in order to limit Schnatter's chances of buying back a [[majority stake]] in the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/jul/26/papa-john-schnatter-lawsuit-racial-slur|title='Papa John' files lawsuit against Papa John's pizza chain}}</ref>\n\nOn February 4, 2019, it was announced that the activist hedge fund [[Starboard Value]], which had played a large role in turning around the troubled [[Olive Garden]] restaurant chain, would be investing $200 million into Papa John's Pizza and that Starboard could possibly invest an additional $50 million by March 29, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/04/investing/papa-johns-starboard-investment/index.html|title=Papa John's gets a $200 million investment and new chairman|last=Business|first=Danielle Wiener-Bronner, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> It was simultaneously announced that Starboard Value CEO [[Jeff Smith (hedge fund manager)|Jeff Smith]] would become the new Papa John's chairman and that Anthony Sanfilippo, former CEO of the gaming company [[Pinnacle Entertainment]], would be another addition to the company's board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/noahkirsch/2019/02/04/after-failing-to-secure-buyout-papa-johns-announces-200-million-investment-from-hedge-fund-starboard-value/|title=After Failing To Secure Buyout, Papa John's Announces $200 Million Deal With Former Olive Garden Investor|last=Kirsch|first=Noah|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> Following that announcement, Ritchie said that he hoped the deal would put an end to the ongoing feud with Schnatter, telling CNBC's David Faber, \"Obviously, we're very hopeful that we can bring John along.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/05/papa-johns-ceo-is-hopeful-schnatter-will-come-along-post-starboard.html|title=Papa John's CEO is 'hopeful' Schnatter will come along post-Starboard|last=Lucas|first=Amelia|date=2019-02-05|website=cnbc.com|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> However, Schnatter has expressed concerns that Ritchie is not the right executive for Papa John's.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-papa-john-s-lawsuit/papa-johns-founder-says-successor-not-right-fit-for-ceo-idUSKBN1KG2ST|title=Papa John's founder says successor not right fit for CEO|work=Reuters|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, 2019, Papa John's announced a settlement with Schnatter under which he will resign from the company's board of directors at the company's annual meeting on April 30 or when a mutually acceptable independent director is appointed to replace him, whichever comes first.<ref>{{cite web |title=Papa John's, Schnatter reach settlement agreement |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/papa-john-s-schnatter-reach-settlement-agreement-1.4322747 |website=[[CTV News]] |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> Schnatter agreed to dismiss two lawsuits filed against the company and to withdraw his plan to run for a seat on the board at the annual meeting. Papa John's agreed to remove the \"acting in concert\" provisions from its \"poison pill\" plan that prevented Schnatter from communicating with other company shareholders. Schnatter, who still controls 31% of Papa John's shares, issued a statement saying he was \"thankful that I've been able to resolve these important issues\" and hoped everyone could now \"focus on the company's business without the need for additional litigation\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mulier |first1=Thomas |last2=Moffat |first2=Anne Riley |title=Papa John's Founder John Schnatter to Quit Board |url=http://fortune.com/2019/03/05/papa-john-schnatter-resigns-board/ |website=Fortune |accessdate=6 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The company also agreed to remove a requirement that Starboard Value, which owns about 10% of the company, must vote in favor of the incumbent board.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/papa-johns-reaches-settlement-agreement-112632337.html |title=Papa John's founder Schnatter to exit board in settlement |first1=Soundarya |last1=J |first2=Jessica |last2=DiNapoli |agency=[[Reuters]] |website=[[Yahoo Finance]] |date=March 5, 2019 |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, 2019, it was announced that NBA Hall of Famer [[Shaquille O'Neal]] will join Papa John's board of directors and become a spokesman for the brand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/22/business/shaq-papa-johns-trnd/index.html|title=Shaq is joining Papa John's board of directors|last=Business|first=Nathaniel Meyersohn, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/business/consumer/papa-john-s-has-new-spokesperson-shaquille-o-neal-n986396</ref>\n\nOn August 27, 2019, Papa John's announced [[Arby's]] President Rob Lynch would be the new CEO replacing Steve Ritchie, who was handpicked by founder John Schnatter to succeed him in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lucas |first1=Amelia |title=Papa John's names Arby's President Rob Lynch as CEO, shares jump 7% |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/27/papa-johns-names-arbys-president-as-ceo.html |website=CNBC |language=en |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=={{anchor|Business ventures}}Operations==\n\n[[File:Papa Johns Springboro OH USA.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Papa John's in [[Springboro, Ohio]], built specifically for home delivery]]\n[[File:Papa John's Locations.svg|thumb|350x350px|Countries with Papa John's Pizza (as of 2018)]]\nPapa John's primarily takes carryout and delivery orders, although some stores have tables and chairs for dining in.\n\n[[Franchising|Franchise]] owners pay a one-off franchise fee of $25,000 per restaurant, then a royalty fee of 5% of net sales, plus a charge for advertising of 8% of net sales. The company requires franchisees to have net worth of at least $250,000, the approximate amount of investment needed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/how-much-it-costs-to-open-a-papa-johns-2015-5 |title=How much it costs to open a Papa John's - Business Insider |website=Business Insider UK |date=May 22, 2015|author=Hayley Peterson|accessdate= July 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://company.papajohns.com/franchise_opps/us_requirements.shtm |title=U.S. Franchising Opportunities \u2013 Requirements & Fees \u2013 Papa John's Pizza |publisher=Papa John's International, Inc. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502155324/http://company.papajohns.com/franchise_opps/us_requirements.shtm |archive-date=May 2, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Corporate operations look over franchisees to ensure brand consistency. Papa John's International is a publicly traded company, with 25% of its shares owned by John Schnatter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ownership Profile |url=http://ir.papajohns.com/ownership-profile.cfm |website=Papa John's International, Inc. |accessdate=January 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106044736/http://ir.papajohns.com/ownership-profile.cfm |archive-date=January 6, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2002, Papa John's became the first national pizza chain to make [[Internet|online]] ordering available to all of its U.S. customers.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.just-food.com/news/papa-johns-first-pizza-chain-to-offer-nationwide-online-ordering_id74126.aspx |accessdate=February 18, 2007 |title=USA: Papa John's first pizza chain to offer nationwide online ordering |date=January 10, 2002 |website=Just Food}}</ref> Most other national chains later added online ordering to their services. On July 10, 2004, Papa John's controlled an estimated 6.6% of the market, according to Technomic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-189205.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921061518/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-189205.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 21, 2013 |title=Domino's Prepares to Go Public as Pizza Chains Are Challenged |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=July 10, 2004 |first=Michael |last=Barbaro |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, it was reported by the Associated Press that the company was testing a \"Papa Priority\" $2.99 fee that lets people jump to the head of the line for their pizza order.<ref>{{cite news |last=Staff |first=Writer |url=https://apnews.com/b15860cc4179421d89ca92d6bfa14e79/Papa-John's-testing-$2.99-fee-for-%22priority%22-orders |title=Papa John's testing $2.99 fee for priority orders |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 1, 2017 |accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Franchises outside the U.S.===\n====Europe====\nPapa John's has operated in the United Kingdom since 2001. In July 2015, the company had 300 shops in the UK,<ref>{{cite news |first=Rachel |last=Swatman |date=June 29, 2015 |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/brand-or-agency/2015/6/papa-john-launches-300th-uk-store-by-leading-army-of-staff-to-world-record-title-386608 |title=Papa John launches 300th UK store by leading army of staff to pizza making world record |work=[[Guinness World Records]] |accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> although in 2010 it had plans for the number rising to between 400 and 500 within the next five years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/7970736/Papa-Johns-after-slice-of-Dominos-pizza-action.html |title=Papa-Johns after slice of Domino's pizza action. |last=Wilson |first=Amy |date=August 29, 2010 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=April 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's operates throughout Ireland, with its head office at Ballybrit, [[County Galway]]. The company has over 50 locations and operates mobile units around the country. The franchises are often located adjacent to [[Supermacs]] fast food outlets.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://supermacs.ie |title=Supermac's |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202065841/http://supermacs.ie/ |archive-date=February 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Spain]] is the second most important [[Europe]]an market for Papa John's. The chain has been operating in Spain since 2016, and due to its fast growth it already had 42 restaurants by late 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.papajohns.es/Locales|title=Pizza cerca de mi - Papa John's Espa\u00f1a|website=papajohns.es}}</ref> In particular, the restaurants achieved a significant presence in the [[Community of Madrid|Madrid]] province with more than half of the Spanish restaurants being located there. Papa John's expects to open at least 100 restaurants just in the province of Madrid, as well as expanding to other regions across Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eleconomista.es/empresas-finanzas/noticias/7599060/05/16/Papa-Johns-International-celebra-la-inauguracion-de-su-primer-restaurante-en-Madrid-Espana.html|title=Papa John\u00b4s International celebra la inauguraci\u00f3n de su primer restaurante en Madrid (Espa\u00f1a) - elEconomista.es|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's also operates in Russia and Belarus with plans to expand to several other Eastern European and Central Asian Countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-papa-john-s-expansion/papa-johns-russian-franchisee-to-expand-in-central-asia-poland-idUSKCN1B41PL|title=Papa John's Russian franchisee to expand in Central Asia, Poland|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Papa John's cars 1.jpg|thumb|Papa John's delivery cars in [[Novosibirsk]], Russia.]]\nPapa John's restaurants in Portugal have closed or no longer operate under the brand name. Some of these locations still serve pizza, though the master-franchise Rest-Smart filed for bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite journal |page=4440 |title=Processo: 1028/09.0TYLSB Insolv\u00eancia pessoa colectiva (Apresenta\u00e7\u00e3o) Data: 11-01-2010 |language=Portuguese |journal=Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica |volume=2 |issue=20 |date=January 29, 2010 |url=http://dre.pt/pdf2sdip/2010/01/020000000/0444004440.pdf |accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019 it was announced that Papa John's will enter the German market by taking over [[Halle (Saale)|Halle/Salle]]-based Uno Pizza and converting their stores into Papa John's. The aim is to open up to 250 locations in Germany in the upcoming five to seven years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.food-service.de/maerkte/news/pj-western-papa-johns-kommt-nach-deutschland-42905|title=PJ Western: Papa John's kommt nach Deutschland|website=https://www.food-service.de/|language=de|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\nIn Poland, Papa John's opened their first location in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://businessinsider.com.pl/lifestyle/jedzenie/pizzerie-papa-johns-wchodza-na-polski-rynek/5lnz5mr|title=Legendarne pizzerie Papa John's wkraczaj\u0105 do Polski|last=Polska|first=Business Insider|last2=Pa\u017a 17 11:59|first2=20|date=2017-10-20|website=Business Insider|language=pl|access-date=2019-05-22|last3=74 728}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Papa John's opened their first restaurant in Kazakhstan, which became the 46th country in the world where the chain is represented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vlast.kz/novosti/29146-set-piccerij-papa-johns-otkryvaet-pervyj-restoran-v-kazahstane.html|title=\u0421\u0435\u0442\u044c \u043f\u0438\u0446\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439 Papa John\u2019s \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043d \u0432 \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435|website=vlast.kz|language=ru|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the Netherlands Papa John's opened its doors in 2019, starting in Amsterdam and expending further through the Netherlands in 2019.<ref>https://www.lunchroom.nl/nieuwe-vestiging-van-papa-johns-in-amsterdam</ref>\n\n[[File:Papa John's scooters.jpg|thumb|A Papa John's Pizza restaurant in [[Hoofddorp]], [[Netherlands]]]]\n\n====Latin America====\n[[File:PapaJohnsRD.JPG|thumb|200px|Papa John's in [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]]]\nPapa John's operates in 13 Latin American countries, including Colombia, Chile, and Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20170410005263/en/Papa-John%E2%80%99s-International-Opens-100th-Restaurant-Mexico|title=Papa John's International Opens 100th Restaurant in Mexico|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodbev.com/news/papa-johns-to-open-more-pizza-restaurants-in-chile-and-spain/|title=Papa John's to open more pizza restaurants in Chile and Spain|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://medellinliving.com/papa-johns-pizza/|title=Papa John's Pizza Opens in Medell\u00edn|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Asia====\nIn 2018, Papa John's sold ownership of its 34 corporately-owned locations in Beijing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apnews.com/aaa83693d5fd4aba83c8eae32c3f8827|title=Papa John's International Completes Sale of China Restaurants|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's opened its first store in Lahore, Pakistan in early 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190129005194/en/Papa-John's-International-Celebrates-Restaurant-Lahore-Pakistan|title=Papa John's International Celebrates First Restaurant in Lahore, Pakistan|website=Business Wire|date=2019-01-29|language=en|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\n===Sponsorships===\nOn March 30, 2006, [[Six Flags]] announced that its parks' pizza would exclusively be from Papa John's. In turn, Six Flags received an annual sponsorship and promotional opportunities from Papa John's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.qsrmagazine.com/news/papa-johns-be-exclusive-pizza-vendor-six-flags-parks|title=Papa John's to be Exclusive Pizza Vendor at Six Flags Parks|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref> Papa John's is also the official pizza supplier of the [[Olympic Oval|Olympic Speedskating Oval]] in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada.\n\nIn November 2006, Papa John's signed with [[ESPN]] Regional Television to become the title sponsor of the annual [[PapaJohns.com Bowl]], a college post-season football [[bowl game]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], which Papa John's continued to sponsor through 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2015/12/whats_the_future_hold_for_birmingham_bowl_without_title_sponsor.html |title=What's the future hold for Birmingham Bowl without title sponsor? |newspaper=[[Birmingham News]] |date=December 15, 2015 |first=Brandon |last=Marcello}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Papa John's signed an agreement to be the Official Pizza Sponsor of the [[National Football League]] and [[Super Bowl XLV|Super Bowls XLV]], [[Super Bowl XLVI|XLVI]] and [[Super Bowl XLVII|XLVII]].<ref name=nfl>{{cite press release |url=http://ir.papajohns.com/releasedetail.cfm?releaseid=616659|title=Papa John's Pizza Expands Relationship with NFL by Signing Multi-Year Deal to Be Official Pizza Sponsor of NFL in Canada, Mexico and United Kingdom|date=October 20, 2011|accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref> In 2011, Papa John's became the official Pizza Sponsor of the NFL in Canada, Mexico and the United Kingdom.<ref name=nfl/> In October 2012, [[Denver Broncos]] quarterback [[Peyton Manning]] became a franchisee in the [[Denver]] area for Papa John's, and also purchased 21 franchises in the area.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-10-27/broncos-peyton-manning-to-own-21-papa-john-s-pizza-franchises.html |title=Broncos' Peyton Manning to Own 21 Papa John's Pizza Franchises |date=October 27, 2012 |accessdate=October 29, 2012 |first=Nancy |last=Kercheval |website=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref> In July 2013, Papa John's announced it had become the Official Pizza Partner of [[The Football League]] in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/footballleaguenews/20130715/papa-johns-announces-football-league-sponsorship_2293334_3238361 |title=Papa John's announces Football League sponsorship |date=July 15, 2013 |publisher=[[The Football League]] |accessdate=August 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718100856/http://www.football-league.co.uk/footballleaguenews/20130715/papa-johns-announces-football-league-sponsorship_2293334_3238361 |archive-date=July 18, 2013}}</ref> The sponsorship ended after the 2017 season when Pizza Hut became the official pizza of the NFL in February 2018.\n\nThe company was the former beneficiary of the [[naming rights]] to [[Cardinal Stadium|Papa John's Cardinal Stadium]] used by the [[Louisville Cardinals|University of Louisville's football team]], in exchange for Schnatter personally donating $5 million for the rights.<ref name=insider>{{cite web |url=https://insiderlouisville.com/education-community/papa-john-koch-brother-give-multimillion-dollar-gifts-u-l/ |author=George, Stephen |title=Papa John, Koch brother give multimillion-dollar gifts to U of L |publisher=Insider Louisville |date=March 10, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref> Schnatter made a further $10 million donation for the stadium's expansion,<ref name=insider/> and extended the naming rights to the year 2040. The Papa John's name was taken off the stadium in July 2018, after Schnatter's resignation from the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wkyt.com/content/news/University-of-Louisville-removes-Papa-Johns-name-from-Cardinal-Stadium-488123961.html|title=University of Louisville removes Papa John's name from Cardinal Stadium|first=WKYT News|last=Staff|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\nPapa John's received attention in May 2008 when a [[Washington, D.C.]] franchise distributed [[T-shirt]]s making fun of [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] star player [[LeBron James]] at a [[NBA Playoffs|playoff]] game against the [[Washington Wizards]]. Photographs of the shirts quickly spread from the Internet<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sogoodblog.com/2008/05/03/papa-johns-pizza-hates-the-state-of-ohio/|title=Does Papa John's Pizza Hate the State of Ohio?|publisher=So Good Blog|date=May 3, 2008|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref> to Cleveland television. Increasing awareness of the controversy prompted an apology from the Papa John's national headquarters on May 5.<ref>{{cite news|last=Eick|first=Jon|url=http://www.imediaconnection.com/content/19390.asp|title=How Papa John's averted a WOM disaster|publisher=iMedia Connection|date=May 28, 2008}}</ref> To apologize, Papa John's offered large single-topping pizzas for 23 cents (matching James' [[squad number|jersey number]]) at all locations in [[Greater Cleveland]] and throughout northern Ohio. The chain sold over 172,000 pizzas at 23 cents a piece, with customers waiting in lines outside of some stores for as long as three hours.<ref>{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Zicari|date=May 9, 2008|title=Editors' Picks for Friday from The PD |url=http://blog.cleveland.com/metro/2008/05/editors_picks_for_friday_from_50.html|newspaper=[[Cleveland Plain Dealer]] |accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's also received media attention on January 6, 2012, when an employee typed the phrase \"lady chinky eyes\" on a receipt issued to an [[Asian American]] customer at a restaurant in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-01-07/news/30603058_1_receipt-tweeted-papa-john |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711142037/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-01-07/news/30603058_1_receipt-tweeted-papa-john |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 11, 2012 |title=Papa John's customer: Pizza joint called me 'lady chinky eyes'|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]] |first=Nina |last=Mandell |date=January 7, 2012}}</ref> The employee was fired and the company issued a formal apology.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jordan|last=Chittley|work=Daily Buzz|url=http://ca.news.yahoo.com/blogs/daily-buzz/papa-john-employee-fired-racial-slur-receipt-180158302.html|title=Papa John's employee fired for racial slur on receipt |publisher=[[Yahoo]]|date=January 10, 2012|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref> A manager at the restaurant where the incident occurred told the ''[[New York Post]]'' that the cashier, a teenager, did not intend to offend saying, \"It's a busy place, and it was a way to identify her and her order. You know, we do stuff like that sometimes. We'll write 'the lady with the blue eyes' or 'the guy in the green shirt.' I think the lady put it out there just to get some attention, some people like that type of attention.\"<ref>{{cite news |date=January 8, 2012|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/01/08/woman-claims-papa-johns-used-racial-slur-to-id-her|title=Papa John's Fires Employee For Using Racial Slur To ID Korean Woman On Receipt|publisher=[[WCBS-TV]]|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's CEO [[John Schnatter]] informed shareholders that his business's costs would increase due to the additional expenses associated with the implementation of [[Affordable Care Act|the Affordable Care Act]], and that franchisees would pass those expenses on to the consumer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tau|first=Byron|title=Papa John's: 'Obamacare' will raise pizza prices |url=http://www.politico.com/politico44/2012/08/papa-johns-obamacare-will-raise-pizza-prices-131331.html|accessdate=August 14, 2012 |newspaper=[[Politico]]|date=August 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nJohn Schnatter's claim that a reverse in [[National Football League|NFL]] viewer ratings (supposedly because of the [[NFL kneeling controversy]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://truthout.org/articles/a-year-since-trump-s-election-as-explained-by-terrible-pizza/ |title=William Rivers Pitt - The Year Since Trump's Election, as Explained by Bad Pizza|work=truth-out.org}}</ref> had directly led to decreased same-store sales across Papa John's franchises was extensively reported in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/papa-john-slams-nfl-following-national-anthem-protests-2017-11|title=Papa John slams NFL for 'poor leadership' after player protests lead to sales slump|work=Business Insider}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/21250448/nfl-sponsor-papa-john-not-happy-anthem-protests|title=Papa John's boss: NFL protests hurting sales|publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref> It was estimated that Schnatter's personal holdings in the chain had lost millions of dollars in value.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/noahkirsch/2017/11/01/papa-johns-founder-net-worth-falls-70-million-in-hours-blames-nfl-protests/|title=Papa John Loses Dough: Pizza Chain Founder Loses $70 Million In Hours, Blames NFL|first=Noah|last=Kirsch|work=Forbes}}</ref> Papa John's disavowed statements by [[white supremacist]] groups expressing support for the brand in the wake of Schnatter's comments.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://qz.com/1137806/a-complete-list-of-brands-white-supremacists-have-given-their-unwanted-endorsement/ |title=A complete list of brands white supremacists have given their unwanted endorsement |last=Coren |first=Michael J. |date=November 30, 2017|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quarts]] |publisher=[[Atlantic Media]] |access-date=July 14, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nA media report surfaced on July 11, 2018, claiming that Schnatter had used a racial epithet in a conference call the previous May, along with graphic descriptions of violence against racial minorities. ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine reported that a media agency working with Papa John's severed its relationship with the company following the report. Steve Ritchie, who had replaced Schnatter as CEO, responded with a memo stating that \"racism has no place at Papa John's,\" and a company spokesman wrote in an email that Papa John's \"condemns racism\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Giammona |first1=Craig |last2=Boyle |first2=Matthew |date=July 11, 2018 |title=Papa John's slides after founder finds himself in hot water again |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/topstocks/papa-johns-slides-after-founder-finds-himself-in-hot-water-again/ar-AAzV5Mk?ocid=spartanntp |work=Bloomberg |access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref> The same day, Schnatter admitted to using the racial epithet during the conference call and resigned as chairman of the company's board of directors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/10/papa-johns-founder-john-schnatter-resigns-as-chairman-of-company-boar.html|title=Papa John's shares surge after founder John Schnatter resigns as chairman following N-word comment|first=Sarah Whitten, Yen Nee|last=Lee|date=July 12, 2018|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-44803163|title=Papa John's founder Schnatter resigns over N-word use - BBC News|date=July 12, 2018|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref> On July 13, 2018, top executives of the company decided to remove Schnatter's image from marketing materials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/07/13/news/companies/papa-johns-schnatter-out/index.html|title=Papa John's to remove founder's image from ads - CNN Money|date=July 13, 2018|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Litigation==\nIn 1997, [[Pizza Hut]] filed a lawsuit against Papa John's based on a series of advertisements that compared the ingredients of Papa John's and its competitors. Pizza Hut successfully argued that Papa John's slogan did not constitute statements of literal fact \u2013 that \"fresher ingredients\" do not necessarily account for a \"better\" pizza. This ruling was overturned in 2000 when Papa John's appealed the decision. Although the jury's decision on the misleading advertising was upheld, the appeals court determined that Pizza Hut failed to prove, under the requirements of the [[Lanham Act]], that the misleading advertising and [[puffery]] had a material effect on consumers' purchasing decisions.\n\nIn 2012, the company was the subject of a [[class action|class-action lawsuit]] for allegedly sending over 500,000 unwanted text messages to customers.<ref name=\"latimes 2012\">{{cite news| last= Hsu| first=Tiffany| title=Papa John's faces $250-million class action spam lawsuit | work=[[L. A. Times]] | date=14 November 2012 | url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/nov/14/business/la-fi-mo-papa-johns-spam-lawsuit-appreciation-20121114 | access-date=15 March 2019}}</ref> The suit sought over $250 million in damages, though the company settled to pay $16.5 million, awarding claimants up to $50 in damages, and a free, large, one-topping pizza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Papa John's Agrees to $16.5M Text Spam Class Action Settlement |first=Sarah |last=Mirando |date=May 20, 2013 |publisher=Top Class Actions |url=http://www.topclassactions.com/lawsuit-settlements/lawsuit-news/4146-papa-john-s-agrees-to-16-5m-text-spam-class-action-settlement |accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Papa John's agreed to pay $12.3 million to settle a class-action lawsuit in which the company was accused of undercompensating 19,000 delivery drivers in the states of [[Arizona]], [[Florida]], [[Illinois]], [[Maryland]], [[Missouri]] and [[North Carolina]]. The complaint stated that the flat reimbursement amount per delivery for drivers failed to equal minimum wage.<ref>{{cite news |last=McNair |first=James |title=Papa John's To Settle Claims It Underpaid Delivery Drivers |url=http://wfpl.org/papa-johns-to-settle-claims-it-underpaid-delivery-drivers/ |publisher=[[WFPL]] |date=August 7, 2015 |accessdate=August 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, [[Panera Bread]] filed a lawsuit with the U.S. Eastern District Court in Missouri accusing Papa John's of stealing digital trade secrets and proprietary data management strategies by hiring Michael Nettles, a former Panera executive who was in charge of the chain's corporate digital technologies deployment.<ref name=lcj-2016jul21>{{cite news |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/crime/2016/07/21/panera-papa-johns-exec-took-trade-secrets/87377258/ |title=Panera: Papa John's exec took trade secrets |newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=July 21, 2016 |first=Jere |last=Downs}}</ref> In August, a Federal judge issued a restraining order, preventing Nettles from reporting to work at Papa John's while the case was active.<ref name=lcj-2016aug13>{{cite news |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/money/companies/2016/08/13/papa-johns-exec-out-pending-panera-secrets-suit/88673140/ |title=Papa John's exec out pending Panera secrets suit |newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=August 13, 2016 |first=Jere |last=Downs}}</ref> Later that year, Panera told the Federal court that it had agreed to drop the lawsuit in December 2016. Details that led to the lawsuit being dropped were not made public.<ref name=\"law360-2016dec22\">{{cite news |url=https://www.law360.com/articles/876287/panera-agrees-to-drop-noncompete-suit-against-papa-john-s |title=Panera Agrees To Drop Noncompete Suit Against Papa John's |website=[[Law360]] |date=December 22, 2016 |first=Matthew |last=Perlman}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Companies|Food}}\n* [[Cardinal Stadium]] \u2013 a [[American football|football]] stadium on the campus of the [[University of Louisville]] formerly bearing the company's name via a [[naming rights]] agreement\n* [[List of pizza chains]]\n* [[List of pizza chains of the United States]]\n* [[List of pizza franchises]]\n* [[List of pizza varieties by country]]\n* [[List of major employers in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n* [[List of the largest fast food restaurant chains]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = Papa John's Pizza\n| symbol = PZZA\n| sec_cik = PZZA\n| yahoo = PZZA\n| google = PZZA\n}}\n\n{{Pizza chains}}\n{{Fast-food chains of the United States}}\n{{UK Food}}\n{{Food chains in South Korea}}\n\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Indiana]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Fast-food chains of the United States]]\n[[Category:Fast-food franchises]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of Canada]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of the United States]]\n[[Category:Pizza franchises]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1984]]\n[[Category:1993 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Jeffersontown, Kentucky]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Papa John\u2019s Pizza, Inc.\n| trading_name =\n| logo = Papa John's Logo 2019.svg\n| image = Papa johns.jpg\n| image_caption = A Papa John's in [[Front Royal, Virginia]]\n| type = [[Public Company|Public]]\n| traded_as = {{NASDAQ|PZZA}}<br />[[S&P 400|S&P 400 Component]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1984|10|02}}\n| location = [[Jeffersontown, Kentucky]], U.S.\n| num_locations = 5,395<br />(December 2019)<ref name=10K/>\n| founder = [[John Schnatter]]\n| key_people = Rob Lynch <br />{{small|(President and CEO)}}<br />Karlin Linhardt<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ir.papajohns.com/corporate-governance/management|date= Aug 27, 2019|title=Papa John's names new global chief marketing officer|work=[[Nation's Restaurant News]]|accessdate=March 28, 2019}}</ref><br />{{small|[[Chief marketing officer|CMO]]}}\n| industry = Pizza, Pizza Delivery\n| revenue = {{Decrease}} US$1.619 billion {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K>{{cite report |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/901491/000155837020001393/pzza-20191229x10kcbc0c2.htm|title=Papa John's International, Inc. Form 10-K for 2019 |website=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n| products = [[Pizza]], [[Chicken as food|chicken wings]], [[dessert]]\n| operating_income = {{Decrease}} US$24.535 million {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| net_income = {{Increase}} US$4.866 million {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| assets = {{Increase}} US$730.721 million {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| equity = {{Decrease}} -US$316.656 million {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| num_employees = ~16,500 {{small|(FY December 29, 2019)}}<ref name=10K/>\n| homepage = {{url|papajohns.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Papa John's''' is an American [[pizza]] restaurant franchise. On April 1, 2020 they played a prank on facebook saying 3 large pizzas to whomever comments<ref>https://m.facebook.com/109450634042799/photos/a.109458124042050/109458960708633/?type=3</ref> It's the fourth largest [[pizza delivery]] [[Chain store#Restaurant chains|restaurant chain]] in the United States,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pmq.com/December-2014/Pizza-PowerThe-2015-Pizza-Power-Report/ |title=The 2015 Pizza Power Report |last=Hynum |first=Rick |date=2014 |website=Pizza Magazine |publisher=PMQ |access-date=26 October 2018 |quote= }}</ref> with headquarters in [[Jeffersontown, Kentucky]], a suburb of [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Papa John's Pizza logo.svg|thumb|Previous logo]]\nThe Papa John's restaurant was founded in 1984 when \"Papa\" [[John Schnatter]] knocked out a broom closet in the back of his father's tavern, Mick's Lounge, in [[Jeffersonville, Indiana]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wolfson|first1=Andrew|title=The real Papa John: Pizza entrepreneur John Schnatter makes no apologies for wealth, success, Obamacare remarks {{!}} Math whiz mixed pizza passion, finance |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/money/2013/01/13/the-real-papa-john-pizza-entrepreneur-john-schnatter-m/28936389/ |accessdate=March 22, 2017|work=[[The Courier-Journal]]|date=January 13, 2013}}</ref> He then sold his [[Chevrolet Camaro (second generation)|1971 Camaro Z28]] to purchase [[US$]]1,600 worth of used pizza equipment and began selling pizzas to the tavern's customers out of the converted closet.<ref name=\"PJStory\" /> His pizzas proved sufficiently popular that a year later he moved into an adjoining space. Dipping sauce specifically for pizza was invented by Papa John's Pizza that same year, and has since become popular when eating pizza, especially the crust.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shrikant|first1=Adit|title=How Dipping Sauce for Pizza Became Oddly Necessary |url=https://www.eater.com/2017/7/27/16021832/pizza-dipping-sauce-papa-johns-garlic-dominos-sauce|website=Eater|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|accessdate=July 28, 2017}}</ref> The company went public in 1993. A year later it had 500 stores, and by 1997 it had opened 1,500 stores.<ref>{{cite web|title=This Marketing Insight Made Papa John's A Household Name|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/papa-johns-marketing-insight-2014-5?IR=T/|website=Business Insider|date=May 21, 2014|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> In 2009, Schnatter reacquired the Camaro back after offering a reward of $250,000 for the car.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Found: Papa John's Long-Lost Camaro! Kentucky Man Receives $250,000 Finder's Fee |date=August 25, 2009 |publisher=Papa John's |url=http://ir.papajohns.com/releasedetail.cfm?ReleaseID=404954 |accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''PMQ Pizza Magazine'' said in December 2016 that the company was the third-largest take-out and pizza delivery restaurant chain in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pizza Power 2017 \u2013 A State of the Industry Report|url=http://www.pmq.com/December-2016/Pizza-Power-2017-A-State-of-the-Industry-Report/|website=PMQ Pizza Magazine|date=December 2016|accessdate=April 20, 2017}}</ref> (According to PMQ, [[Little Caesars]] is the third-largest pizza chain; however, it does not deliver.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/05/31/why-little-caesars-doesnt-need-delivery-to-compete-in-the-restaurant-industry.html |title=This is why Little Caesars won't be investing in delivery |newspaper=Cnbc.com |date=May 31, 2017|author=Sarah Whitten|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref>) The company's net profitability though, is far behind its main competitors. In 2014 its net margin was 4.6% of total sales, whereas [[Domino's Pizza]]'s net margin was 8.2% and [[Yum! Brands]], which owns [[Pizza Hut]], was 7.9%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://marketrealist.com/2015/12/comparing-papa-johns-net-margins-quick-service-big-guns |title=Papa John's Marketing and Promotional Strategies: What's in the Oven? |newspaper=Market Realist |date=December 10, 2015|author=Ralph Nathan|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref> Company headquarters are in Jeffersontown, Kentucky, a community within the [[Louisville Metro Council|merged government]] of Louisville.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/doc/241428416.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov%2007,%202007&author=&pub=Courier%20-%20Journal&edition=&startpage=&desc=Jeffersontown%20to%20dedicate%20new%20bike%20and%20walking%20path%20Saturday |title=Jeffersontown to dedicate new bike and walking path Saturday |newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=November 7, 2007 |page=C7 |accessdate=December 6, 2012 |quote=Papa John's office is in Jeffersontown |url-access=subscription  |first=Chris |last=Otts |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140326131049/http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/doc/241428416.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov%2007,%202007&author=&pub=Courier%20-%20Journal&edition=&startpage=&desc=Jeffersontown%20to%20dedicate%20new%20bike%20and%20walking%20path%20Saturday |archive-date=March 26, 2014 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.papajohns.com/pizzachallenge/index.shtm |title=Papa's Specialty Pizza Challenge |website=Papa John's Pizza |accessdate=December 6, 2012 |quote=Papa John's International Inc., 2002 Papa John's Blvd, Louisville, KY 40299 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100801210325/http://www.papajohns.com/pizzachallenge/index.shtm |archive-date=August 1, 2010 |url-status=dead |author=<!--not specified-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite map |url=http://www2.census.gov/geo/maps/dc10map/GUBlock/st21_ky/place/p2140222_jeffersontown/DC10BLK_P2140222_001.pdf |title=2010 Census \u2013 Census Block Map (Index): Jeffersontown city, KY |publisher=[[U.S. Census Bureau]] |date=2010 |accessdate=December 7, 2012}}</ref> Its slogan is \"Better Ingredients. Better Pizza. Papa John's.\"\n\nPapa John's has over 5,199 establishments\u20144,456 franchised restaurants operating domestically in all 50 states and in 44 countries and territories. Papa John's operates 246 \"company owned stores\" under joint ventures and 35 units in Beijing and North China.<ref name=10K/> In September 2012 the 4,000th Papa John's Pizza restaurant opened, in [[New Hyde Park, New York]]. The company celebrated the event by giving away 4,000 free pizzas to customers throughout New York City.<ref name=\"PJStory\">{{cite web |url=http://www.papajohns.co.uk/our-story/history.aspx |title=The Papa John's Story |publisher=Papa John's (GB) Ltd |accessdate=August 2, 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130710004930/http://www.papajohns.co.uk/our-story/history.aspx |archive-date=July 10, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=http://ir.papajohns.com/releaseDetail.cfm?ReleaseID=706740 |title=Papa John's Celebrates Opening of 4,000th Restaurant Worldwide |accessdate=September 16, 2012 |date=September 13, 2012 |website=Papa John's International, Inc.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/franchises/papajohnsintlinc/282662 |title=Papa John's Int'l. Inc. Franchise Information |magazine=[[Entrepreneur (magazine)|Entrepreneur]] |accessdate=September 16, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe company announced on December 21, 2017, that John Schnatter would step down as CEO of Papa John's Pizza on January 1, 2018, to be replaced as CEO by current company President [[Steve Ritchie (businessman)|Steve Ritchie]] with Schnatter remaining chairman at the time.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/2017/12/21/papa-johns-ceo-john-schnatter-steps-down/974917001/ |title=Papa John's CEO, pizza titan John Schnatter, steps down |accessdate=December 21, 2017 |date=December 21, 2017 |author=Zlati Meyer}}</ref> In February 2018, Papa John's and the NFL mutually agreed to end their sponsorship agreement after Schnatter's criticism of the NFL made headlines.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/early-lead/wp/2018/02/27/papa-johns-nfl-end-sponsorship-agreement-after-anthem-protest-controversy/|title=Pizza Hut scores NFL pizza sponsorship deal after Papa John's bows out|last=Boren|first=Cindy |date=February 28, 2018|work=Washington Post|access-date=March 1, 2018|last2=Flaherty|first2=Bryan|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nOn July 11, 2018, news outlets reported that during a conference call with Papa Johns' marketing agency Laundry Services, Schnatter had used the word \"nigger\" by saying \"[[Colonel Sanders]] called blacks niggers and Sanders never faced public backlash.\" Schnatter alleged that referencing the quote by the [[KFC]] founder was meant to convey his dislike for racism.<ref>{{cite news|first=Noah|last=Kirsch |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/noahkirsch/2018/07/11/papa-johns-founder-john-schnatter-allegedly-used-n-word-on-conference-call/ |title=Papa John's Founder Used N-Word On Conference Call|work=[[Forbes]]|publisher=[[Forbes Media]]|location=New York City|date=July 11, 2018}}</ref> After the call, the owner of the marketing agency moved to end their contract with Papa John's. Schnatter resigned as chairman of the board on the same day the incident was reported.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/07/11/news/companies/papa-johns-pizza-john-schnatter/index.html|title=Papa John's founder resigns as chairman after using N-word on conference call|first=Nathaniel|last=Meyersohn|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter the incident, Ritchie apologized in an open letter and ordered the company's workforce to undergo bias and diversity training.<ref>{{citation|title=Papa John's orders workers to undergo bias and diversity training|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/nation-now/2018/08/24/papa-johns-bias-diversity-training/1085908002/}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title=Papa John's CEO Attempts Damage Control But Not An Apology|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/papa-johns-damage-control_n_5b49237de4b0bc69a78749ea}}</ref>\n\nOn July 26, 2018, [[John Schnatter]] filed a [[lawsuit]] against Papa John's Pizza to give him access to the company's [[financial statements|books]] and records after they fired him from the company after the teleconference call scandal. He describes the company's procedures as an \"unexplained and heavy-handed way\" to cut ties between him and the company that he founded. In addition to preventing him from accessing information, the corporation has also implemented a [[Shareholder rights plan|poison pill strategy]] in order to limit Schnatter's chances of buying back a [[majority stake]] in the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/jul/26/papa-john-schnatter-lawsuit-racial-slur|title='Papa John' files lawsuit against Papa John's pizza chain}}</ref>\n\nOn February 4, 2019, it was announced that the activist hedge fund [[Starboard Value]], which had played a large role in turning around the troubled [[Olive Garden]] restaurant chain, would be investing $200 million into Papa John's Pizza and that Starboard could possibly invest an additional $50 million by March 29, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/02/04/investing/papa-johns-starboard-investment/index.html|title=Papa John's gets a $200 million investment and new chairman|last=Business|first=Danielle Wiener-Bronner, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> It was simultaneously announced that Starboard Value CEO [[Jeff Smith (hedge fund manager)|Jeff Smith]] would become the new Papa John's chairman and that Anthony Sanfilippo, former CEO of the gaming company [[Pinnacle Entertainment]], would be another addition to the company's board.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/noahkirsch/2019/02/04/after-failing-to-secure-buyout-papa-johns-announces-200-million-investment-from-hedge-fund-starboard-value/|title=After Failing To Secure Buyout, Papa John's Announces $200 Million Deal With Former Olive Garden Investor|last=Kirsch|first=Noah|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> Following that announcement, Ritchie said that he hoped the deal would put an end to the ongoing feud with Schnatter, telling CNBC's David Faber, \"Obviously, we're very hopeful that we can bring John along.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/05/papa-johns-ceo-is-hopeful-schnatter-will-come-along-post-starboard.html|title=Papa John's CEO is 'hopeful' Schnatter will come along post-Starboard|last=Lucas|first=Amelia|date=2019-02-05|website=cnbc.com|access-date=2019-02-06}}</ref> However, Schnatter has expressed concerns that Ritchie is not the right executive for Papa John's.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-papa-john-s-lawsuit/papa-johns-founder-says-successor-not-right-fit-for-ceo-idUSKBN1KG2ST|title=Papa John's founder says successor not right fit for CEO|work=Reuters|accessdate=16 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 5, 2019, Papa John's announced a settlement with Schnatter under which he will resign from the company's board of directors at the company's annual meeting on April 30 or when a mutually acceptable independent director is appointed to replace him, whichever comes first.<ref>{{cite web |title=Papa John's, Schnatter reach settlement agreement |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/business/papa-john-s-schnatter-reach-settlement-agreement-1.4322747 |website=[[CTV News]] |accessdate=6 March 2019}}</ref> Schnatter agreed to dismiss two lawsuits filed against the company and to withdraw his plan to run for a seat on the board at the annual meeting. Papa John's agreed to remove the \"acting in concert\" provisions from its \"poison pill\" plan that prevented Schnatter from communicating with other company shareholders. Schnatter, who still controls 31% of Papa John's shares, issued a statement saying he was \"thankful that I've been able to resolve these important issues\" and hoped everyone could now \"focus on the company's business without the need for additional litigation\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mulier |first1=Thomas |last2=Moffat |first2=Anne Riley |title=Papa John's Founder John Schnatter to Quit Board |url=http://fortune.com/2019/03/05/papa-john-schnatter-resigns-board/ |website=Fortune |accessdate=6 March 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The company also agreed to remove a requirement that Starboard Value, which owns about 10% of the company, must vote in favor of the incumbent board.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/papa-johns-reaches-settlement-agreement-112632337.html |title=Papa John's founder Schnatter to exit board in settlement |first1=Soundarya |last1=J |first2=Jessica |last2=DiNapoli |agency=[[Reuters]] |website=[[Yahoo Finance]] |date=March 5, 2019 |access-date=March 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, 2019, it was announced that NBA Hall of Famer [[Shaquille O'Neal]] will join Papa John's board of directors and become a spokesman for the brand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/03/22/business/shaq-papa-johns-trnd/index.html|title=Shaq is joining Papa John's board of directors|last=Business|first=Nathaniel Meyersohn, CNN|website=CNN|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref><ref>https://www.nbcnews.com/business/consumer/papa-john-s-has-new-spokesperson-shaquille-o-neal-n986396</ref>\n\nOn August 27, 2019, Papa John's announced [[Arby's]] President Rob Lynch would be the new CEO replacing Steve Ritchie, who was handpicked by founder John Schnatter to succeed him in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lucas |first1=Amelia |title=Papa John's names Arby's President Rob Lynch as CEO, shares jump 7% |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/08/27/papa-johns-names-arbys-president-as-ceo.html |website=CNBC |language=en |date=27 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=={{anchor|Business ventures}}Operations==\n\n[[File:Papa Johns Springboro OH USA.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Papa John's in [[Springboro, Ohio]], built specifically for home delivery]]\n[[File:Papa John's Locations.svg|thumb|350x350px|Countries with Papa John's Pizza (as of 2018)]]\nPapa John's primarily takes carryout and delivery orders, although some stores have tables and chairs for dining in.\n\n[[Franchising|Franchise]] owners pay a one-off franchise fee of $25,000 per restaurant, then a royalty fee of 5% of net sales, plus a charge for advertising of 8% of net sales. The company requires franchisees to have net worth of at least $250,000, the approximate amount of investment needed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/how-much-it-costs-to-open-a-papa-johns-2015-5 |title=How much it costs to open a Papa John's - Business Insider |website=Business Insider UK |date=May 22, 2015|author=Hayley Peterson|accessdate= July 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://company.papajohns.com/franchise_opps/us_requirements.shtm |title=U.S. Franchising Opportunities \u2013 Requirements & Fees \u2013 Papa John's Pizza |publisher=Papa John's International, Inc. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120502155324/http://company.papajohns.com/franchise_opps/us_requirements.shtm |archive-date=May 2, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Corporate operations look over franchisees to ensure brand consistency. Papa John's International is a publicly traded company, with 25% of its shares owned by John Schnatter.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ownership Profile |url=http://ir.papajohns.com/ownership-profile.cfm |website=Papa John's International, Inc. |accessdate=January 1, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106044736/http://ir.papajohns.com/ownership-profile.cfm |archive-date=January 6, 2016 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2002, Papa John's became the first national pizza chain to make [[Internet|online]] ordering available to all of its U.S. customers.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.just-food.com/news/papa-johns-first-pizza-chain-to-offer-nationwide-online-ordering_id74126.aspx |accessdate=February 18, 2007 |title=USA: Papa John's first pizza chain to offer nationwide online ordering |date=January 10, 2002 |website=Just Food}}</ref> Most other national chains later added online ordering to their services. On July 10, 2004, Papa John's controlled an estimated 6.6% of the market, according to Technomic.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-189205.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130921061518/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-189205.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 21, 2013 |title=Domino's Prepares to Go Public as Pizza Chains Are Challenged |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=July 10, 2004 |first=Michael |last=Barbaro |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, it was reported by the Associated Press that the company was testing a \"Papa Priority\" $2.99 fee that lets people jump to the head of the line for their pizza order.<ref>{{cite news |last=Staff |first=Writer |url=https://apnews.com/b15860cc4179421d89ca92d6bfa14e79/Papa-John's-testing-$2.99-fee-for-%22priority%22-orders |title=Papa John's testing $2.99 fee for priority orders |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 1, 2017 |accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Franchises outside the U.S.===\n====Europe====\nPapa John's has operated in the United Kingdom since 2001. In July 2015, the company had 300 shops in the UK,<ref>{{cite news |first=Rachel |last=Swatman |date=June 29, 2015 |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/brand-or-agency/2015/6/papa-john-launches-300th-uk-store-by-leading-army-of-staff-to-world-record-title-386608 |title=Papa John launches 300th UK store by leading army of staff to pizza making world record |work=[[Guinness World Records]] |accessdate=June 3, 2016}}</ref> although in 2010 it had plans for the number rising to between 400 and 500 within the next five years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/retailandconsumer/7970736/Papa-Johns-after-slice-of-Dominos-pizza-action.html |title=Papa-Johns after slice of Domino's pizza action. |last=Wilson |first=Amy |date=August 29, 2010 |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=April 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's operates throughout Ireland, with its head office at Ballybrit, [[County Galway]]. The company has over 50 locations and operates mobile units around the country. The franchises are often located adjacent to [[Supermacs]] fast food outlets.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://supermacs.ie |title=Supermac's |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202065841/http://supermacs.ie/ |archive-date=February 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Spain]] is the second most important [[Europe]]an market for Papa John's. The chain has been operating in Spain since 2016, and due to its fast growth it already had 42 restaurants by late 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.papajohns.es/Locales|title=Pizza cerca de mi - Papa John's Espa\u00f1a|website=papajohns.es}}</ref> In particular, the restaurants achieved a significant presence in the [[Community of Madrid|Madrid]] province with more than half of the Spanish restaurants being located there. Papa John's expects to open at least 100 restaurants just in the province of Madrid, as well as expanding to other regions across Spain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eleconomista.es/empresas-finanzas/noticias/7599060/05/16/Papa-Johns-International-celebra-la-inauguracion-de-su-primer-restaurante-en-Madrid-Espana.html|title=Papa John\u00b4s International celebra la inauguraci\u00f3n de su primer restaurante en Madrid (Espa\u00f1a) - elEconomista.es|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's also operates in Russia and Belarus with plans to expand to several other Eastern European and Central Asian Countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-papa-john-s-expansion/papa-johns-russian-franchisee-to-expand-in-central-asia-poland-idUSKCN1B41PL|title=Papa John's Russian franchisee to expand in Central Asia, Poland|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Papa John's cars 1.jpg|thumb|Papa John's delivery cars in [[Novosibirsk]], Russia.]]\nPapa John's restaurants in Portugal have closed or no longer operate under the brand name. Some of these locations still serve pizza, though the master-franchise Rest-Smart filed for bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite journal |page=4440 |title=Processo: 1028/09.0TYLSB Insolv\u00eancia pessoa colectiva (Apresenta\u00e7\u00e3o) Data: 11-01-2010 |language=Portuguese |journal=Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica |volume=2 |issue=20 |date=January 29, 2010 |url=http://dre.pt/pdf2sdip/2010/01/020000000/0444004440.pdf |accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019 it was announced that Papa John's will enter the German market by taking over [[Halle (Saale)|Halle/Salle]]-based Uno Pizza and converting their stores into Papa John's. The aim is to open up to 250 locations in Germany in the upcoming five to seven years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.food-service.de/maerkte/news/pj-western-papa-johns-kommt-nach-deutschland-42905|title=PJ Western: Papa John's kommt nach Deutschland|website=https://www.food-service.de/|language=de|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\nIn Poland, Papa John's opened their first location in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://businessinsider.com.pl/lifestyle/jedzenie/pizzerie-papa-johns-wchodza-na-polski-rynek/5lnz5mr|title=Legendarne pizzerie Papa John's wkraczaj\u0105 do Polski|last=Polska|first=Business Insider|last2=Pa\u017a 17 11:59|first2=20|date=2017-10-20|website=Business Insider|language=pl|access-date=2019-05-22|last3=74 728}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Papa John's opened their first restaurant in Kazakhstan, which became the 46th country in the world where the chain is represented.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vlast.kz/novosti/29146-set-piccerij-papa-johns-otkryvaet-pervyj-restoran-v-kazahstane.html|title=\u0421\u0435\u0442\u044c \u043f\u0438\u0446\u0446\u0435\u0440\u0438\u0439 Papa John\u2019s \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0432\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430\u043d \u0432 \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0435|website=vlast.kz|language=ru|access-date=2019-12-14}}</ref>\n\nIn the Netherlands Papa John's opened its doors in 2019, starting in Amsterdam and expending further through the Netherlands in 2019.<ref>https://www.lunchroom.nl/nieuwe-vestiging-van-papa-johns-in-amsterdam</ref>\n\n[[File:Papa John's scooters.jpg|thumb|A Papa John's Pizza restaurant in [[Hoofddorp]], [[Netherlands]]]]\n\n====Latin America====\n[[File:PapaJohnsRD.JPG|thumb|200px|Papa John's in [[Santo Domingo]], [[Dominican Republic]]]]\nPapa John's operates in 13 Latin American countries, including Colombia, Chile, and Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20170410005263/en/Papa-John%E2%80%99s-International-Opens-100th-Restaurant-Mexico|title=Papa John's International Opens 100th Restaurant in Mexico|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodbev.com/news/papa-johns-to-open-more-pizza-restaurants-in-chile-and-spain/|title=Papa John's to open more pizza restaurants in Chile and Spain|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://medellinliving.com/papa-johns-pizza/|title=Papa John's Pizza Opens in Medell\u00edn|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Asia====\nIn 2018, Papa John's sold ownership of its 34 corporately-owned locations in Beijing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apnews.com/aaa83693d5fd4aba83c8eae32c3f8827|title=Papa John's International Completes Sale of China Restaurants|accessdate=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's opened its first store in Lahore, Pakistan in early 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20190129005194/en/Papa-John's-International-Celebrates-Restaurant-Lahore-Pakistan|title=Papa John's International Celebrates First Restaurant in Lahore, Pakistan|website=Business Wire|date=2019-01-29|language=en|access-date=2019-02-05}}</ref>\n\n===Sponsorships===\nOn March 30, 2006, [[Six Flags]] announced that its parks' pizza would exclusively be from Papa John's. In turn, Six Flags received an annual sponsorship and promotional opportunities from Papa John's.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.qsrmagazine.com/news/papa-johns-be-exclusive-pizza-vendor-six-flags-parks|title=Papa John's to be Exclusive Pizza Vendor at Six Flags Parks|accessdate=14 February 2019}}</ref> Papa John's is also the official pizza supplier of the [[Olympic Oval|Olympic Speedskating Oval]] in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]], Canada.\n\nIn November 2006, Papa John's signed with [[ESPN]] Regional Television to become the title sponsor of the annual [[PapaJohns.com Bowl]], a college post-season football [[bowl game]] in [[Birmingham, Alabama]], which Papa John's continued to sponsor through 2010.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2015/12/whats_the_future_hold_for_birmingham_bowl_without_title_sponsor.html |title=What's the future hold for Birmingham Bowl without title sponsor? |newspaper=[[Birmingham News]] |date=December 15, 2015 |first=Brandon |last=Marcello}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Papa John's signed an agreement to be the Official Pizza Sponsor of the [[National Football League]] and [[Super Bowl XLV|Super Bowls XLV]], [[Super Bowl XLVI|XLVI]] and [[Super Bowl XLVII|XLVII]].<ref name=nfl>{{cite press release |url=http://ir.papajohns.com/releasedetail.cfm?releaseid=616659|title=Papa John's Pizza Expands Relationship with NFL by Signing Multi-Year Deal to Be Official Pizza Sponsor of NFL in Canada, Mexico and United Kingdom|date=October 20, 2011|accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref> In 2011, Papa John's became the official Pizza Sponsor of the NFL in Canada, Mexico and the United Kingdom.<ref name=nfl/> In October 2012, [[Denver Broncos]] quarterback [[Peyton Manning]] became a franchisee in the [[Denver]] area for Papa John's, and also purchased 21 franchises in the area.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-10-27/broncos-peyton-manning-to-own-21-papa-john-s-pizza-franchises.html |title=Broncos' Peyton Manning to Own 21 Papa John's Pizza Franchises |date=October 27, 2012 |accessdate=October 29, 2012 |first=Nancy |last=Kercheval |website=[[Bloomberg News]]}}</ref> In July 2013, Papa John's announced it had become the Official Pizza Partner of [[The Football League]] in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.football-league.co.uk/footballleaguenews/20130715/papa-johns-announces-football-league-sponsorship_2293334_3238361 |title=Papa John's announces Football League sponsorship |date=July 15, 2013 |publisher=[[The Football League]] |accessdate=August 2, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718100856/http://www.football-league.co.uk/footballleaguenews/20130715/papa-johns-announces-football-league-sponsorship_2293334_3238361 |archive-date=July 18, 2013}}</ref> The sponsorship ended after the 2017 season when Pizza Hut became the official pizza of the NFL in February 2018.\n\nThe company was the former beneficiary of the [[naming rights]] to [[Cardinal Stadium|Papa John's Cardinal Stadium]] used by the [[Louisville Cardinals|University of Louisville's football team]], in exchange for Schnatter personally donating $5 million for the rights.<ref name=insider>{{cite web |url=https://insiderlouisville.com/education-community/papa-john-koch-brother-give-multimillion-dollar-gifts-u-l/ |author=George, Stephen |title=Papa John, Koch brother give multimillion-dollar gifts to U of L |publisher=Insider Louisville |date=March 10, 2015|accessdate=September 18, 2016}}</ref> Schnatter made a further $10 million donation for the stadium's expansion,<ref name=insider/> and extended the naming rights to the year 2040. The Papa John's name was taken off the stadium in July 2018, after Schnatter's resignation from the company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wkyt.com/content/news/University-of-Louisville-removes-Papa-Johns-name-from-Cardinal-Stadium-488123961.html|title=University of Louisville removes Papa John's name from Cardinal Stadium|first=WKYT News|last=Staff|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Media coverage==\nPapa John's received attention in May 2008 when a [[Washington, D.C.]] franchise distributed [[T-shirt]]s making fun of [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] star player [[LeBron James]] at a [[NBA Playoffs|playoff]] game against the [[Washington Wizards]]. Photographs of the shirts quickly spread from the Internet<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sogoodblog.com/2008/05/03/papa-johns-pizza-hates-the-state-of-ohio/|title=Does Papa John's Pizza Hate the State of Ohio?|publisher=So Good Blog|date=May 3, 2008|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref> to Cleveland television. Increasing awareness of the controversy prompted an apology from the Papa John's national headquarters on May 5.<ref>{{cite news|last=Eick|first=Jon|url=http://www.imediaconnection.com/content/19390.asp|title=How Papa John's averted a WOM disaster|publisher=iMedia Connection|date=May 28, 2008}}</ref> To apologize, Papa John's offered large single-topping pizzas for 23 cents (matching James' [[squad number|jersey number]]) at all locations in [[Greater Cleveland]] and throughout northern Ohio. The chain sold over 172,000 pizzas at 23 cents a piece, with customers waiting in lines outside of some stores for as long as three hours.<ref>{{cite news|first=Peter|last=Zicari|date=May 9, 2008|title=Editors' Picks for Friday from The PD |url=http://blog.cleveland.com/metro/2008/05/editors_picks_for_friday_from_50.html|newspaper=[[Cleveland Plain Dealer]] |accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's also received media attention on January 6, 2012, when an employee typed the phrase \"lady chinky eyes\" on a receipt issued to an [[Asian American]] customer at a restaurant in New York City.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-01-07/news/30603058_1_receipt-tweeted-papa-john |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711142037/http://articles.nydailynews.com/2012-01-07/news/30603058_1_receipt-tweeted-papa-john |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 11, 2012 |title=Papa John's customer: Pizza joint called me 'lady chinky eyes'|newspaper=[[New York Daily News]] |first=Nina |last=Mandell |date=January 7, 2012}}</ref> The employee was fired and the company issued a formal apology.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jordan|last=Chittley|work=Daily Buzz|url=http://ca.news.yahoo.com/blogs/daily-buzz/papa-john-employee-fired-racial-slur-receipt-180158302.html|title=Papa John's employee fired for racial slur on receipt |publisher=[[Yahoo]]|date=January 10, 2012|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref> A manager at the restaurant where the incident occurred told the ''[[New York Post]]'' that the cashier, a teenager, did not intend to offend saying, \"It's a busy place, and it was a way to identify her and her order. You know, we do stuff like that sometimes. We'll write 'the lady with the blue eyes' or 'the guy in the green shirt.' I think the lady put it out there just to get some attention, some people like that type of attention.\"<ref>{{cite news |date=January 8, 2012|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2012/01/08/woman-claims-papa-johns-used-racial-slur-to-id-her|title=Papa John's Fires Employee For Using Racial Slur To ID Korean Woman On Receipt|publisher=[[WCBS-TV]]|accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPapa John's CEO [[John Schnatter]] informed shareholders that his business's costs would increase due to the additional expenses associated with the implementation of [[Affordable Care Act|the Affordable Care Act]], and that franchisees would pass those expenses on to the consumer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Tau|first=Byron|title=Papa John's: 'Obamacare' will raise pizza prices |url=http://www.politico.com/politico44/2012/08/papa-johns-obamacare-will-raise-pizza-prices-131331.html|accessdate=August 14, 2012 |newspaper=[[Politico]]|date=August 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nJohn Schnatter's claim that a reverse in [[National Football League|NFL]] viewer ratings (supposedly because of the [[NFL kneeling controversy]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://truthout.org/articles/a-year-since-trump-s-election-as-explained-by-terrible-pizza/ |title=William Rivers Pitt - The Year Since Trump's Election, as Explained by Bad Pizza|work=truth-out.org}}</ref> had directly led to decreased same-store sales across Papa John's franchises was extensively reported in November 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/papa-john-slams-nfl-following-national-anthem-protests-2017-11|title=Papa John slams NFL for 'poor leadership' after player protests lead to sales slump|work=Business Insider}}<br />{{cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/21250448/nfl-sponsor-papa-john-not-happy-anthem-protests|title=Papa John's boss: NFL protests hurting sales|publisher=ESPN.com}}</ref> It was estimated that Schnatter's personal holdings in the chain had lost millions of dollars in value.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/noahkirsch/2017/11/01/papa-johns-founder-net-worth-falls-70-million-in-hours-blames-nfl-protests/|title=Papa John Loses Dough: Pizza Chain Founder Loses $70 Million In Hours, Blames NFL|first=Noah|last=Kirsch|work=Forbes}}</ref> Papa John's disavowed statements by [[white supremacist]] groups expressing support for the brand in the wake of Schnatter's comments.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://qz.com/1137806/a-complete-list-of-brands-white-supremacists-have-given-their-unwanted-endorsement/ |title=A complete list of brands white supremacists have given their unwanted endorsement |last=Coren |first=Michael J. |date=November 30, 2017|website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quarts]] |publisher=[[Atlantic Media]] |access-date=July 14, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n\nA media report surfaced on July 11, 2018, claiming that Schnatter had used a racial epithet in a conference call the previous May, along with graphic descriptions of violence against racial minorities. ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine reported that a media agency working with Papa John's severed its relationship with the company following the report. Steve Ritchie, who had replaced Schnatter as CEO, responded with a memo stating that \"racism has no place at Papa John's,\" and a company spokesman wrote in an email that Papa John's \"condemns racism\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Giammona |first1=Craig |last2=Boyle |first2=Matthew |date=July 11, 2018 |title=Papa John's slides after founder finds himself in hot water again |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/money/topstocks/papa-johns-slides-after-founder-finds-himself-in-hot-water-again/ar-AAzV5Mk?ocid=spartanntp |work=Bloomberg |access-date=July 11, 2018}}</ref> The same day, Schnatter admitted to using the racial epithet during the conference call and resigned as chairman of the company's board of directors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/07/10/papa-johns-founder-john-schnatter-resigns-as-chairman-of-company-boar.html|title=Papa John's shares surge after founder John Schnatter resigns as chairman following N-word comment|first=Sarah Whitten, Yen Nee|last=Lee|date=July 12, 2018|accessdate=July 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-44803163|title=Papa John's founder Schnatter resigns over N-word use - BBC News|date=July 12, 2018|work=[[BBC Online]]|accessdate=July 12, 2018}}</ref> On July 13, 2018, top executives of the company decided to remove Schnatter's image from marketing materials.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/07/13/news/companies/papa-johns-schnatter-out/index.html|title=Papa John's to remove founder's image from ads - CNN Money|date=July 13, 2018|accessdate=July 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Litigation==\nIn 1997, [[Pizza Hut]] filed a lawsuit against Papa John's based on a series of advertisements that compared the ingredients of Papa John's and its competitors. Pizza Hut successfully argued that Papa John's slogan did not constitute statements of literal fact \u2013 that \"fresher ingredients\" do not necessarily account for a \"better\" pizza. This ruling was overturned in 2000 when Papa John's appealed the decision. Although the jury's decision on the misleading advertising was upheld, the appeals court determined that Pizza Hut failed to prove, under the requirements of the [[Lanham Act]], that the misleading advertising and [[puffery]] had a material effect on consumers' purchasing decisions.\n\nIn 2012, the company was the subject of a [[class action|class-action lawsuit]] for allegedly sending over 500,000 unwanted text messages to customers.<ref name=\"latimes 2012\">{{cite news| last= Hsu| first=Tiffany| title=Papa John's faces $250-million class action spam lawsuit | work=[[L. A. Times]] | date=14 November 2012 | url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/nov/14/business/la-fi-mo-papa-johns-spam-lawsuit-appreciation-20121114 | access-date=15 March 2019}}</ref> The suit sought over $250 million in damages, though the company settled to pay $16.5 million, awarding claimants up to $50 in damages, and a free, large, one-topping pizza.<ref>{{cite news |title=Papa John's Agrees to $16.5M Text Spam Class Action Settlement |first=Sarah |last=Mirando |date=May 20, 2013 |publisher=Top Class Actions |url=http://www.topclassactions.com/lawsuit-settlements/lawsuit-news/4146-papa-john-s-agrees-to-16-5m-text-spam-class-action-settlement |accessdate=January 17, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Papa John's agreed to pay $12.3 million to settle a class-action lawsuit in which the company was accused of undercompensating 19,000 delivery drivers in the states of [[Arizona]], [[Florida]], [[Illinois]], [[Maryland]], [[Missouri]] and [[North Carolina]]. The complaint stated that the flat reimbursement amount per delivery for drivers failed to equal minimum wage.<ref>{{cite news |last=McNair |first=James |title=Papa John's To Settle Claims It Underpaid Delivery Drivers |url=http://wfpl.org/papa-johns-to-settle-claims-it-underpaid-delivery-drivers/ |publisher=[[WFPL]] |date=August 7, 2015 |accessdate=August 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, [[Panera Bread]] filed a lawsuit with the U.S. Eastern District Court in Missouri accusing Papa John's of stealing digital trade secrets and proprietary data management strategies by hiring Michael Nettles, a former Panera executive who was in charge of the chain's corporate digital technologies deployment.<ref name=lcj-2016jul21>{{cite news |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/news/crime/2016/07/21/panera-papa-johns-exec-took-trade-secrets/87377258/ |title=Panera: Papa John's exec took trade secrets |newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=July 21, 2016 |first=Jere |last=Downs}}</ref> In August, a Federal judge issued a restraining order, preventing Nettles from reporting to work at Papa John's while the case was active.<ref name=lcj-2016aug13>{{cite news |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/money/companies/2016/08/13/papa-johns-exec-out-pending-panera-secrets-suit/88673140/ |title=Papa John's exec out pending Panera secrets suit |newspaper=[[The Courier-Journal]] |date=August 13, 2016 |first=Jere |last=Downs}}</ref> Later that year, Panera told the Federal court that it had agreed to drop the lawsuit in December 2016. Details that led to the lawsuit being dropped were not made public.<ref name=\"law360-2016dec22\">{{cite news |url=https://www.law360.com/articles/876287/panera-agrees-to-drop-noncompete-suit-against-papa-john-s |title=Panera Agrees To Drop Noncompete Suit Against Papa John's |website=[[Law360]] |date=December 22, 2016 |first=Matthew |last=Perlman}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|United States|Companies|Food}}\n* [[Cardinal Stadium]] \u2013 a [[American football|football]] stadium on the campus of the [[University of Louisville]] formerly bearing the company's name via a [[naming rights]] agreement\n* [[List of pizza chains]]\n* [[List of pizza chains of the United States]]\n* [[List of pizza franchises]]\n* [[List of pizza varieties by country]]\n* [[List of major employers in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n* [[List of the largest fast food restaurant chains]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = Papa John's Pizza\n| symbol = PZZA\n| sec_cik = PZZA\n| yahoo = PZZA\n| google = PZZA\n}}\n\n{{Pizza chains}}\n{{Fast-food chains of the United States}}\n{{UK Food}}\n{{Food chains in South Korea}}\n\n[[Category:1984 establishments in Indiana]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1984]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Fast-food chains of the United States]]\n[[Category:Fast-food franchises]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of Canada]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Pizza chains of the United States]]\n[[Category:Pizza franchises]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1984]]\n[[Category:1993 initial public offerings]]\n[[Category:Jeffersontown, Kentucky]]\n", "name_user": "Papa John's International", "label": "safe", "comment": "This edit is from Papa John's International team based in the UK - the April Fool's post is a scam, we are working on removing it", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Papa_John%27s_Pizza"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Schick", "text_new": "[[File: Schick thomas 2012.jpg | thumb | Thomas Schick, Oberwolfach 2012]]\n'''Thomas Schick''' (born 22 May 1969 in [[Alzey]]) is a German mathematician, specializing in algebraic topology and differential geometry.\n\n==Education and career==\nSchick studied mathematics and physics at the [[Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz]], where he received in 1994 his [[Diplom]] in mathematics and in 1996 his PhD ([[Promotion (Germany)|Promotion]]) under the supervision of [[Wolfgang L\u00fcck]] with thesis ''Analysis on Manifolds of Bounded Geometry, Hodge-deRham Isomorphism and <math>L^2</math>-Index Theorem''.<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=27755}}</ref> As a [[postdoc]] he was from 1996 to 1998 at the [[University of M\u00fcnster]] and from 1998 to 2000 an assistant professor at [[Pennsylvania State University]], where he worked with [[Nigel Higson]] and [[John Roe (mathematician)|John Roe]]. Schick received his [[habilitation]] in 2000 from the University of M\u00fcnster and is since 2001 a professor for pure mathematics at the [[University of G\u00f6ttingen]].\n\nHis research deals with topological invariants, ''e.g.'' <math>L^2</math>-invarianten and those invariants which result from the [[K-theory]] of [[operator algebra]]s. Such invariants arise in generalizations of the [[Atiyah-Singer index theorem]]. \n\nSchick, with Wolfgang L\u00fcck, introduced the strong Atiyah conjecture. Given a discrete group G, the Atiyah conjecture states that the <math>L^2</math>-[[Betti number]]s of a finite [[CW-complex]] that has fundamental group G are integers, provided that G is torsion-free; furthermore, in the general case, the <math>L^2</math>-Betti numbers are rational numbers with denominators determined by the finite subgroups of G. In 2007 Schick, with Peter Linnell, proved a theorem which established conditions under which the Atiyah conjecture for a torsion-free group G implies the Atiyah conjecture for every finite extension of G; furthermore, they proved that the conditions are satisfied for a certain class of groups.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schick, T.|author2=Linnell, P.|title=Finite group extensions and the Atiyah conjecture|journal=Journal of the American Mathematical Society|volume=20|year=2007|pages=1003\u20131061|url=http://www.uni-math.gwdg.de/schick/publ/extAtiyah.html|arxiv=math/0403229|doi=10.1090/S0894-0347-07-00561-9}}</ref> In 2000 Schick proved the Atiyah conjecture for a large class of special cases.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schick, T.|title=Integrality of <math>L^2</math> Betti numbers|journal=Mathematische Annalen|volume=317|issue=4|year=2000|pages=727\u2013750|doi=10.1007/PL00004421|arxiv=math/0001101}}</ref>. In 2007 he presented a method which proved the Baum-Connes conjecture for the full braid groups, and for other classes of groups which arise as (finite) extensions for which the Baum-Connes conjecture is known to be true.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schick, T.|title=Finite group extensions and the Baum-Connes conjecture|journal=Geometry and Topology|volume=11|year=2007|pages=1767\u20131775|doi=10.2140/gt.2007.11.1767}} [https://arxiv.org/abs/math.KT/0209165 arXiv preprint]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas Schick: Finite group extensions and the Baum-Connes conjecture|website=Schick's website at the University of G\u00f4ttingen (uni-math.gwdg.de)|url=http://www.uni-math.gwdg.de/schick/publ/BC_finite_ext.html}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s there were proofs of many special cases of the Gromov-Lawson-Rosenberg conjecture concerning criteria for the existence of a metric with positive [[scalar curvature]]; in 1997 Schick published the first counterexample.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schick, T.|title=A counterexample to the (unstable) Gromov-Lawson-Rosenberg conjecture|journal=Topology|volume=37|year=1998|pages=1165\u20131168|doi=10.1016/s0040-9383(97)00082-7}} [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0403063 arXiv preprint]</ref>\n\nHe is the coordinator of the Courant Research Center's ''Strukturen h\u00f6herer Ordnung in der Mathematik'' (Structures of Higher Order in Mathematics) at the [[University of G\u00f6ttingen]].<ref>{{cite web|website=G\u00f6ttinger Tageblatt|title=Neuartige Probleme der Mathematik l\u00f6sen, G\u00f6ttingen, Courant Forschungszentrum|date=19 May 2009|url=http://www.goettinger-tageblatt.de/Nachrichten/Wissen/Wissen-vor-Ort/Neuartige-Probleme-der-Mathematik-loesen}}</ref> A major goal of the research center is the investigation of mathematical structures that could play a role in modern theoretical physics, especially [[string theory]] and [[quantum gravity]].\n\nHe is an editor for [[Mathematische Annalen]]. In 2014 he was an invited speaker with talk ''The topology of scalar curvature'' at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians|ICM]] in [[Seoul]]. In 2016 he became a full member of the [[Akademie der Wissenschaften zu G\u00f6ttingen]].\n\n==Selected publications==\n*''[https://arxiv.org/pdf/1405.4220v2.pdf Topology of scalar curvature.]'' Proc. ICM 2014, Seoul.\n*''[https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0209164 Operator algebras and topology.]'' ICTP Summer School, Triest 2001.\n* with Ulrich Bunke: ''[https://arxiv.org/abs/1011.6663 Differential K-Theory.]''\n* with Ulrich Bunke: ''[https://arxiv.org/abs/0707.0046 Smooth K-Theory.]'' In: ''Ast\u00e9risque.'' No. 328 (2009), 45\u2013135 (2010). {{ISBN|978-2-85629-289-1}}.\n* with Bernhard Hanke and Wolfgang Steimle: ''The space of metrics of positive scalar curvature.'' Publ. Math. Inst. Hautes \u00c9tudes Sci. 120 (2014), 335\u2013367. {{doi|10.1007/s10240-014-0062-9}}\n* with Hanke: ''Enlargeability and index theory.'' J. Differential Geom. 74 (2006), no. 2, 293\u2013320. [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0403257 Arxiv]\n* with Dodziuk, Linnell, Mathai, Yates: ''Approximating L<sup>2</sup>-invariants and the Atiyah conjecture. Dedicated to the memory of [[J\u00fcrgen K. Moser]].'' Comm. Pure Appl. Math. 56 (2003), no. 7, 839\u2013873. {{doi|10.1002/cpa.10076}}\n* with [[Rostislav Grigorchuk]], Linnell, \u017buk: ''On a question of Atiyah.'' C. R. Acad. Sci. Paris S\u00e9r. I Math. 331 (2000), no. 9, 663\u2013668. [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0009175 Arxiv]\n* with Wolfgang L\u00fcck: ''<math>L^2</math> torsion of hyperbolic manifolds of finite volume.'' In: ''Geometric and Functional Analysis.'' vol. 9, 1999, pp. 518\u2013567, [https://arxiv.org/abs/dg-ga/9707009 Arxiv.]\n*''Integrality of <math>L^2</math> Betti numbers.'' In: ''Mathematische Annalen.'' vol. 317, 2000, pp. 727\u2013750, [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0001101 Arxiv.]\n*''<math>L^2</math>-index theorem for elliptic boundary problems.'' In: ''Pacific J. Math.'' vol. 197, 2001, pp. 423\u2013439, [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/9810133 Arxiv.]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.uni-math.gwdg.de/schick/ Homepage]\n*{{cite web|title=Presseinformation: Antrittsvorlesung des Mathematikers Prof. Dr. Thomas Schick|date=15 January 2002|website=Georg-August-Universit\u00e4t G\u00f6ttingen|url=http://www.uni-goettingen.de/de/3240.html?cid=601}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schick, Thomas}}\n[[Category:Topologists]]\n[[Category:Differential geometers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century German mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz alumni]]\n[[Category:University of G\u00f6ttingen faculty]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "[[File: Schick thomas 2012.jpg | thumb | Thomas Schick, Oberwolfach 2012]]\n'''Thomas Schick''' (born 22 May 1969 in [[Alzey]]) is a German mathematician, specializing in algebraic topology and differential geometry.\n\n==Education and career==\nSchick studied mathematics and physics at the [[Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz]], where he received in 1994 his [[Diplom]] in mathematics and in 1996 his PhD ([[Promotion (Germany)|Promotion]]) under the supervision of [[Wolfgang L\u00fcck]] with thesis ''Analysis on Manifolds of Bounded Geometry, Hodge-deRham Isomorphism and <math>L^2</math>-Index Theorem''.<ref>{{MathGenealogy|id=27755}}</ref> As a [[postdoc]] he was from 1996 to 1998 at the [[University of M\u00fcnster]] and from 1998 to 2000 an assistant professor at [[Pennsylvania State University]], where he worked with [[Nigel Higson]] and [[John Roe (mathematician)|John Roe]]. Schick received his [[habilitation]] in 2000 from the University of M\u00fcnster and is since 2001 a professor for pure mathematics at the [[University of G\u00f6ttingen]].\n\nHis research deals with topological invariants, ''e.g.'' <math>L^2</math>-invarianten and those invariants which result from the [[K-theory]] of [[operator algebra]]s. Such invariants arise in generalizations of the [[Atiyah-Singer index theorem]]. \n\nSchick, with Wolfgang L\u00fcck, introduced the strong Atiyah conjecture. Given a discrete group G, the Atiyah conjecture states that the <math>L^2</math>-[[Betti number]]s of a finite [[CW-complex]] that has fundamental group G are integers, provided that G is torsion-free; furthermore, in the general case, the <math>L^2</math>-Betti numbers are rational numbers with denominators determined by the finite subgroups of G. In 2007 Schick, with Peter Linnell, proved a theorem which established conditions under which the Atiyah conjecture for a torsion-free group G implies the Atiyah conjecture for every finite extension of G; furthermore, they proved that the conditions are satisfied for a certain class of groups.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schick, T.|author2=Linnell, P.|title=Finite group extensions and the Atiyah conjecture|journal=Journal of the American Mathematical Society|volume=20|year=2007|pages=1003\u20131061|url=http://www.uni-math.gwdg.de/schick/publ/extAtiyah.html|arxiv=math/0403229}}</ref> In 2000 Schick proved the Atiyah conjecture for a large class of special cases.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schick, T.|title=Integrality of <math>L^2</math> Betti numbers|journal=Mathematische Annalen|volume=317|issue=4|year=2000|pages=727\u2013750|doi=10.1007/PL00004421|arxiv=math/0001101}}</ref>. In 2007 he presented a method which proved the Baum-Connes conjecture for the full braid groups, and for other classes of groups which arise as (finite) extensions for which the Baum-Connes conjecture is known to be true.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schick, T.|title=Finite group extensions and the Baum-Connes conjecture|journal=Geometry and Topology|volume=11|year=2007|pages=1767\u20131775|doi=10.2140/gt.2007.11.1767}} [https://arxiv.org/abs/math.KT/0209165 arXiv preprint]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas Schick: Finite group extensions and the Baum-Connes conjecture|website=Schick's website at the University of G\u00f4ttingen (uni-math.gwdg.de)|url=http://www.uni-math.gwdg.de/schick/publ/BC_finite_ext.html}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s there were proofs of many special cases of the Gromov-Lawson-Rosenberg conjecture concerning criteria for the existence of a metric with positive [[scalar curvature]]; in 1997 Schick published the first counterexample.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Schick, T.|title=A counterexample to the (unstable) Gromov-Lawson-Rosenberg conjecture|journal=Topology|volume=37|year=1998|pages=1165\u20131168|doi=10.1016/s0040-9383(97)00082-7}} [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0403063 arXiv preprint]</ref>\n\nHe is the coordinator of the Courant Research Center's ''Strukturen h\u00f6herer Ordnung in der Mathematik'' (Structures of Higher Order in Mathematics) at the [[University of G\u00f6ttingen]].<ref>{{cite web|website=G\u00f6ttinger Tageblatt|title=Neuartige Probleme der Mathematik l\u00f6sen, G\u00f6ttingen, Courant Forschungszentrum|date=19 May 2009|url=http://www.goettinger-tageblatt.de/Nachrichten/Wissen/Wissen-vor-Ort/Neuartige-Probleme-der-Mathematik-loesen}}</ref> A major goal of the research center is the investigation of mathematical structures that could play a role in modern theoretical physics, especially [[string theory]] and [[quantum gravity]].\n\nHe is an editor for [[Mathematische Annalen]]. In 2014 he was an invited speaker with talk ''The topology of scalar curvature'' at the [[International Congress of Mathematicians|ICM]] in [[Seoul]]. In 2016 he became a full member of the [[Akademie der Wissenschaften zu G\u00f6ttingen]].\n\n==Selected publications==\n*''[https://arxiv.org/pdf/1405.4220v2.pdf Topology of scalar curvature.]'' Proc. ICM 2014, Seoul.\n*''[https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0209164 Operator algebras and topology.]'' ICTP Summer School, Triest 2001.\n* with Ulrich Bunke: ''[https://arxiv.org/abs/1011.6663 Differential K-Theory.]''\n* with Ulrich Bunke: ''[https://arxiv.org/abs/0707.0046 Smooth K-Theory.]'' In: ''Ast\u00e9risque.'' No. 328 (2009), 45\u2013135 (2010). {{ISBN|978-2-85629-289-1}}.\n* with Bernhard Hanke and Wolfgang Steimle: ''The space of metrics of positive scalar curvature.'' Publ. Math. Inst. Hautes \u00c9tudes Sci. 120 (2014), 335\u2013367. {{doi|10.1007/s10240-014-0062-9}}\n* with Hanke: ''Enlargeability and index theory.'' J. Differential Geom. 74 (2006), no. 2, 293\u2013320. [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0403257 Arxiv]\n* with Dodziuk, Linnell, Mathai, Yates: ''Approximating L<sup>2</sup>-invariants and the Atiyah conjecture. Dedicated to the memory of [[J\u00fcrgen K. Moser]].'' Comm. Pure Appl. Math. 56 (2003), no. 7, 839\u2013873. {{doi|10.1002/cpa.10076}}\n* with [[Rostislav Grigorchuk]], Linnell, \u017buk: ''On a question of Atiyah.'' C. R. Acad. Sci. Paris S\u00e9r. I Math. 331 (2000), no. 9, 663\u2013668. [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0009175 Arxiv]\n* with Wolfgang L\u00fcck: ''<math>L^2</math> torsion of hyperbolic manifolds of finite volume.'' In: ''Geometric and Functional Analysis.'' vol. 9, 1999, pp. 518\u2013567, [https://arxiv.org/abs/dg-ga/9707009 Arxiv.]\n*''Integrality of <math>L^2</math> Betti numbers.'' In: ''Mathematische Annalen.'' vol. 317, 2000, pp. 727\u2013750, [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0001101 Arxiv.]\n*''<math>L^2</math>-index theorem for elliptic boundary problems.'' In: ''Pacific J. Math.'' vol. 197, 2001, pp. 423\u2013439, [https://arxiv.org/abs/math/9810133 Arxiv.]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.uni-math.gwdg.de/schick/ Homepage]\n*{{cite web|title=Presseinformation: Antrittsvorlesung des Mathematikers Prof. Dr. Thomas Schick|date=15 January 2002|website=Georg-August-Universit\u00e4t G\u00f6ttingen|url=http://www.uni-goettingen.de/de/3240.html?cid=601}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schick, Thomas}}\n[[Category:Topologists]]\n[[Category:Differential geometers]]\n[[Category:20th-century German mathematicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century German mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Johannes Gutenberg University Mainz alumni]]\n[[Category:University of G\u00f6ttingen faculty]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEducation and career:Journal cites:, added 1 DOI", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Schick"}
{"title_page": "Siddavesa", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n'''Siddavesa''' kind of religious and traditional folk dance it is also called as ''pursere ka\u1e6d\u1e6dun\u0101'' and ''puru\u1e63a makka\u1e37a ku\u1e47ita''. [[Tulu Gowda]] people of [[Sullia]], [[Belthangady]], [[Puttur, Karnataka|Puttur]] are performing [[full moon]] summer dance in month of Tulu calendar Suggi. In this same month Suggi Nalike also performed.<ref>\nKarvali janapada, Purushotha Bilimale 1990. Mangalagangothri Dakshina Kannada,Siddavesha:Partibhatane mattu Nirasana  P.21</ref> Siddavesha are performing late evening to until morning and visiting all stratum people home.\n\n[[File:Sidda Vesha Performance at Puduvettu - Team.jpg|thumb|Sidda Vesha Performance at Puduvettu]]\n\n==About==\nThe Siddavesa influenced by Natha pantha. They performing in full night enactment with myth mimic, acting, singing and dancing.<ref>Yadupathi Gowda, Gau\u1e0daru-jan\u0101\u1e45ga mattu ku\u1e47ita, Yadupati gau\u1e0da, 2003. Okkaligara Y\u0101ne Gau\u1e0dara S\u0113v\u0101 Sa\u1e45gha, Mangaluru, pg.153</ref> Participants of Siddavesha has different characters, they are interact with themselves and public in different stages of enactment. The three main mythical farce charecters of Siddavesha are Sanyasi, Bhatru and Dasayye.<ref>Puttur Anantharaja Gowda (2015). \"IN PURSUIT OF OUR ROOTS\". Bengaluru: Tenkila Publications</ref>\n\n==Dress and costume==\nThere are number different charecters are performing Dasayya, Bhatru, Sansyasi, [[Koraga people|Koraga]], [[Koti Chennaya]], Beetle Purbu, [[Byari]], [[Pili Yesa|piliyesa]] etc. Dasayya appears in white dhoti and red shawl, holding in his hand with a conch and drum. Head is covered by Mundasu and lenghthed nama in forehead. The Bhartu, a village priest with sacred thread janivara with big knot, white dhoti, smears his body with sandal wood paste and forehead with sandle paste and kunkum.  The sanyasi wear unusual dress, he is main part in this mythical dance, he is fully covered with camouflage platation dried leaves. He is provided with a huge pennies made up of 4-5 wooden sticks tied together which protrudes from his waist. Koraga pastes dark calour to his whole body. Byari with white baniayn, Multi coloured checks printed dhoti and the knot of dhoti bit above the waist so it has been not to have touch the ground, and with tradition toppy.<ref>Janapada kal\u0101 prav\u0113\u015ba, Cakkere \u015biva\u015ba\u1e45kar, 2006. , s\u0101gar prak\u0101\u015bana, be\u1e45ga\u1e37\u016bru. Kar\u0101va\u1e37i karn\u0101\u1e6dakada janapada kalega\u1e37u - sid'dhav\u0113\u1e63a Pg.250</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nAfter sun set the performed artist meets pre decided holy place, mainly in front of daivradhane chavadi or Guttu house. They dress up with using local available costumes after prayer conducted and eldest persons prayes the [[Kadri Manjunath Temple|Kadri Manjunatha]], his local spirits and ancestors. The group of these people move house to house of their region, they performs their court yard. A lamp is lit center of the arena or near the [[Tulasi|Tu\u1e37asi]] ka\u1e6d\u1e6de.<ref>History of Indian Theatre, Volume 2, By Manohar Laxman Varadpande,Pg. 57</ref>\n\nWhen the team arrive at the house of their first performance they serd the Samnyasi into hiding beside the house. The rest of them walk up to the courtyard of the house and wake up the people. They set up a lighted lamp in the centre courtyard and commence dancing around to it with one of them initiating the song as follows:\n::Sidduli\u1e45ga mudduli\u1e45ga - sid'dhav\u0113s\u014d. \n::N\u0101vu y\u0101v\u016bru y\u0101va ta\u1e37a - sid'dhav\u0113s\u014d.\n::N\u0101vu k\u0101\u015b\u012bya ta\u1e37adavru - sid'dhav\u0113s\u014d\nAll the performer performs as per their charecter pre determined by the head of the team, mostly who is eldest. The Samnyasi is left alone on the stage of Siddavesa performance, and he roam arroundthe courtyard holding his pseudo pennies made by 4-5 wooden sticks tied together. He talks unusual sexual words and naughty words. \nWhen they are walking on the street, utter ''\u1e0cimbis\u0101le'', ''\u1e0cimbis\u0101le'' in louder voice. This is the indication of Siidavesa performer are on the way yet to come the house.\n\n==Belief==\nSuppose suggi nalike, performed by mera community accidentally meets Siddavesa on the way, it is consider as bad omen. So the siddavesa performer always utters  ''\u1e0cimbis\u0101le'' chorus on their way to home to home very loudly.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{commons category|Sidda Vesha, Live - Text, Performance, Documentation|Siddavesa }}\n{{Culture of Tulunadu}}\n\n[[Category:Dakshina Kannada district]]\n[[Category:Culture of Tulu Nadu]]\n[[Category:Culture of Mangalore]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n'''Siddavesa''' kind of religious and traditional folk dance it is also called as ''pursere ka\u1e6d\u1e6dun\u0101'' and ''puru\u1e63a makka\u1e37a ku\u1e47ita''. [[Tulu Gowda]] people of [[Sullia]], [[Belthangady]], [[Puttur, Karnataka|Puttur]] are performing [[full moon]] summer dance in month of Tulu calender Suggi. In this same month Suggi Nalike also performed.<ref>\nKarvali janapada, Purushotha Bilimale 1990. Mangalagangothri Dakshina Kannada,Siddavesha:Partibhatane mattu Nirasana  P.21</ref> Siddavesha are performing late evening to until morning and visiting all stratum people home. \n\n[[File:Sidda Vesha Performance at Puduvettu - Team.jpg|thumb|Sidda Vesha Performance at Puduvettu]]\n\n==About==\nThe Siddavesa influenced by Natha pantha. They performing in full night enactment with myth mimic, acting, singing and dancing<ref>Yadupathi Gowda, Gau\u1e0daru-jan\u0101\u1e45ga mattu ku\u1e47ita, Yadupati gau\u1e0da, 2003. Okkaligara Y\u0101ne Gau\u1e0dara S\u0113v\u0101 Sa\u1e45gha, Mangaluru, pg.153</ref>. Participants of Siddavesha has different characters, they are interact with themselves and public in different stages of enactment. The three main mythical farce charecters of Siddavesha are Sanyasi, Bhatru and Dasayye.<ref>Puttur Anantharaja Gowda (2015). \"IN PURSUIT OF OUR ROOTS\". Bengaluru: Tenkila Publications</ref>\n\n==Dress and costume==\nThere are number different charecters are performing Dasayya, Bhatru, Sansyasi, [[Koraga people|Koraga]], [[Koti Chennaya]], Beetle Purbu, [[Byari]], [[Pili Yesa|piliyesa]] etc. Dasayya appears in white dhoti and red shawl, holding in his hand with a conch and drum. Head is covered by Mundasu and lenghthed nama in forehead. The Bhartu, a village priest with sacred thread janivara with big knot, white dhoti, smears his body with sandal wood paste and forehead with sandle paste and kunkum.  The sanyasi wear unusual dress, he is main part in this mythical dance, he is fully covered with camouflage platation dried leaves. He is provided with a huge pennies made up of 4-5 wooden sticks tied together which protrudes from his waist. Koraga pastes dark calour to his whole body. Byari with white baniayn, Multi coloured checks printed dhoti and the knot of dhoti bit above the waist so it has been not to have touch the ground, and with tradition toppy.<ref>Janapada kal\u0101 prav\u0113\u015ba, Cakkere \u015biva\u015ba\u1e45kar, 2006. , s\u0101gar prak\u0101\u015bana, be\u1e45ga\u1e37\u016bru. Kar\u0101va\u1e37i karn\u0101\u1e6dakada janapada kalega\u1e37u - sid'dhav\u0113\u1e63a Pg.250</ref>\n\n==Performance==\nAfter sun set the performed artist meets pre desided holy place, mainly infront of daivradhane chavadi or Guttu house. They dress up with using local availble costumes after prayer conducted and eldest persons prayes the [[Kadri Manjunath Temple|Kadri Manjunatha]], his local spirits and ancestors. The group of these people move house to house of their region, they performes their court yard. A lamp is lit center of the arena or near the [[Tulasi|Tu\u1e37asi]] ka\u1e6d\u1e6de.<ref>History of Indian Theatre, Volume 2, By Manohar Laxman Varadpande,Pg. 57</ref>\n\nWhen the team arrive at the house of their first performance they serd the Samnyasi into hiding beside the house. The rest of them walk up to the courtyard of the house and wake up the people. They set up a lighted lamp in the centre courtyard and commence dancing around to it with one of them initiating the song as follows:\n::Sidduli\u1e45ga mudduli\u1e45ga - sid'dhav\u0113s\u014d. \n::N\u0101vu y\u0101v\u016bru y\u0101va ta\u1e37a - sid'dhav\u0113s\u014d.\n::N\u0101vu k\u0101\u015b\u012bya ta\u1e37adavru - sid'dhav\u0113s\u014d\nAll the performer performs as per their charecter pre determined by the head of the team, mostly who is eldest. The Samnyasi is left alone on the stage of Siddavesa performance, and he roam arroundthe courtyard holding his pseudo pennies made by 4-5 wooden sticks tied together. He talks unusual sexual words and naughty words. \nWhen they are walking on the street, utter ''\u1e0cimbis\u0101le'', ''\u1e0cimbis\u0101le'' in louder voice. This is the indication of Siidavesa performer are on the way yet to come the house.\n\n==Belief==\nSuppose suggi nalike, performed by mera community accidently meets Siddavesa on the way, it is consider as bad omen. So the siddavesa performer always utters  ''\u1e0cimbis\u0101le'' chorus on their way to home to home very loudly.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{commons category|Sidda Vesha, Live - Text, Performance, Documentation|Siddavesa }}\n[[Category:Dakshina Kannada district]]\n[[Category:Culture of Tulu Nadu]]\n[[Category:Culture of Mangalore]]\n{{Culture of Tulunadu}}\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: accidently \u2192 accidentally, availble \u2192 available, calender \u2192 calendar, desided \u2192 decided, infront \u2192 in front, performes \u2192 performs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siddavesa"}
{"title_page": "Abraham Maslow", "text_new": "{{short description|American psychologist}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name             = Abraham Maslow\n|image            = Abraham Maslow.jpg\n|birth_name=Abraham Harold Maslow\n|birth_date       = {{birth-date|April 1, 1908}}\n|birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1970|06|08|1908|04|01}}\n|death_place      = [[Menlo Park, California|Menlo Park]], [[California]], U.S.\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Bertha Goodman Maslow|December 31, 1928}}\n|children         = {{hlist|Ann Maslow|Ellen Maslow}}\n|nationality      = American\n|field            = [[Psychology]]\n|work_institution = {{unbulleted list | [[Cornell University]] | [[Brooklyn College]] | [[Brandeis University]]}}\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n|doctoral_advisor = [[Harry Harlow]]\n|influences       = {{hlist | [[Alfred Adler]] | [[Kurt Goldstein]] | [[Henry Murray]]}}\n|influenced       = {{hlist | [[Douglas McGregor]] | [[Roberto Assagioli]]<ref>Assagioli Roberto. ''Act of Will''. New York: Synthesis Center Press, 2010. Print.</ref> | [[Colin Wilson]] | [[Abbie Hoffman]] | [[Wayne Dyer]] | [[Elliot Aronson]]}}\n|known_for        = [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs]]\n}}\n\n'''Abraham Harold Maslow''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u00e6|z|l|o\u028a}}; April 1, 1908&nbsp;\u2013 June 8, 1970) was an American psychologist who was best known for creating [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs]], a theory of psychological health predicated on fulfilling innate human needs in priority, culminating in self-actualization.<ref name=obit>{{cite news |author= |title=Dr. Abraham Maslow, Founder Of Humanistic Psychology, Dies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/10/archives/dr-abraham-maslow-founder-of-humanistic-psychology-dies.html |quote=Dr. Abraham Maslow, professor of psychology at Brandeis University in Waltham, Mass., and founder of what has come to be known as humanistic psychology, died  of a heart attack. He was 62 years old. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 10, 1970 |accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref> Maslow was a [[psychology]] professor at [[Alliant International University]], [[Brandeis University]], [[Brooklyn College]], [[New School for Social Research]], and [[Columbia University]]. He stressed the importance of focusing on the positive qualities in people, as opposed to treating them as a \"bag of symptoms\".<ref name=hoffman109>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 109.</ref> A ''[[Review of General Psychology]]'' survey, published in 2002, ranked Maslow as the tenth most cited psychologist of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Haggbloom |first=Steven J. |title=The 100 most eminent psychologists of the 20th century |journal=Review of General Psychology |volume=6 |issue=2 |year=2002 |pages=139\u2013152 |doi=10.1037/1089-2680.6.2.139 |url=http://www.apa.org/monitor/julaug02/eminent.aspx |last2=Warnick |first2=Renee |last3=Warnick |first3=Jason E. |last4=Jones |first4=Vinessa K. |last5=Yarbrough |first5=Gary L. |last6=Russell |first6=Tenea M. |last7=Borecky |first7=Chris M. |last8=McGahhey |first8=Reagan |last9=Powell |first9=John L., III| displayauthors = 8 |citeseerx=10.1.1.586.1913 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Youth===\nBorn in 1908 and raised in [[Brooklyn, New York]], Maslow was the oldest of seven children. His parents were first generation [[Jewish]] immigrants from [[Kiev]], then part of the [[Russian Empire]] (now [[Ukraine]]), who fled from Czarist persecution in the early 20th century.<ref name=\"Boeree\">{{cite web|author=Boeree, C.|year=2006|url=http://webspace.ship.edu/cgboer/maslow.html/|title=Abraham Maslow|publisher=Webspace.ship.edu|accessdate=2012-10-21}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZCvrS9DjE68C&pg=PT322&dq=Abraham+Maslow+Kiev&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi8g_XawOXRAhVoIcAKHS7dC8cQ6AEIRTAI#v=onepage&q=Abraham%20Maslow%20Kiev&f=false Dreaming To Some Purpose] by [[Colin Wilson]], [[Arrow Books]], {{ISBN|0099471477}}, 2004</ref> They had decided to live in New York City and in a multiethnic, working-class neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maslow, Abraham H.|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/article-1G2-3456300032/maslow-abraham-h.html}}</ref> His parents were poor and not intellectually focused, but they valued education. He had various encounters with anti-Semitic gangs who would chase and throw rocks at him.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 9.</ref> Maslow and other young people with his background were struggling to overcome such acts of racism and ethnic prejudice in the attempt to establish an idealistic world based on widespread education and economic justice.<ref>Journal of Humanistic Psychology (October 2008), 48 (4), pg. 439-443</ref> The tension outside his home was also felt within it, as he rarely got along with his mother, and eventually developed a strong revulsion towards her. He is quoted as saying, \"What I had reacted to was not only her physical appearance, but also her values and world view, her stinginess, her total selfishness, her lack of love for anyone else in the world &nbsp;\u2013 even her own husband and children &nbsp;\u2013 her narcissism, her Negro prejudice, her exploitation of everyone, her assumption that anyone was wrong who disagreed with her, her lack of friends, her sloppiness and dirtiness...\". He also grew up with few friends other than his cousin Will, and as a result \"...[He] grew up in libraries and among books.\"<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 11.</ref> It was here that he developed his love for reading and learning. He went to [[Boys High School (Brooklyn)|Boys High School]], one of the top high schools in Brooklyn.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 12</ref> Here, he served as the officer to many academic clubs, and became editor of the Latin Magazine. He also edited ''Principia,'' the school's Physics paper, for a year.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 13.</ref> He developed other strengths as well: {{quote|As a young boy, Maslow believed physical strength to be the single most defining characteristic of a true male; hence, he exercised often and took up weight lifting in hopes of being transformed into a more muscular, tough-looking guy, however, he was unable to achieve this due to his humble-looking and chaste figure as well as his studiousness.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Nicholson|first=Ian|title=Giving up maleness: Abraham Maslow, masculinity, and the boundaries of psychology|journal=History of Psychology|date=February 2001|volume=4|issue=1|pages=79\u201391|doi=10.1037/1093-4510.4.1.79|id={{ProQuest|614416838}}}}{{Dead link|date=January 2013}}</ref>}}\n\n===College and university===\nMaslow attended the [[City College of New York]] after high school. In 1926 he began taking legal studies classes at night in addition to his undergraduate course load. He hated it and almost immediately dropped out. In 1927 he transferred to Cornell, but he left after just one semester due to poor grades and high costs.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 30.</ref> He later graduated from City College and went to graduate school at the [[University of Wisconsin]] to study [[psychology]]. In 1928, he married his first cousin Bertha, who was still in high school at the time. The pair had met in Brooklyn years earlier.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 40.</ref> Maslow's psychology training at UW was decidedly experimental-behaviorist.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 39.</ref> At Wisconsin he pursued a line of research which included investigating [[primate]] [[Dominance (ethology)|dominance]] behavior and [[Human sexuality|sexuality]]. Maslow's early experience with behaviorism would leave him with a strong [[positivism|positivist]] mindset.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite journal|author=Hoffman, E|year=2008|title=Abraham Maslow: A Biographer's Reflection|journal=Journal of Humanistic Psychology|volume= 48|issue=4|pages=439\u2013443|doi=10.1177/0022167808320534}}</ref> Upon the recommendation of Professor Hulsey Cason, Maslow wrote his master's thesis on \"learning, retention, and reproduction of verbal material\".<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 44.</ref> Maslow regarded the research as embarrassingly trivial, but he completed his thesis the summer of 1931 and was awarded his master's degree in psychology. He was so ashamed of the thesis that he removed it from the psychology library and tore out its catalog listing.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 45.</ref> However, Professor Cason admired the research enough to urge Maslow to submit it for publication. Maslow's thesis was published as two articles in 1934.\n\n===Academic career===\nHe continued his research at [[Columbia University]] on similar themes. There he found another mentor in [[Alfred Adler]], one of [[Sigmund Freud]]'s early colleagues. From 1937 to 1951, Maslow was on the faculty of [[Brooklyn College]]. His family life and his experiences influenced his psychological ideas. After [[World War II]], Maslow began to question the way psychologists had come to their conclusions, and although he did not completely disagree, he had his own ideas on how to understand the human mind.<ref>[[#Berger|Berger (1983)]], p. 42.</ref> He called his new discipline [[humanistic psychology]]. Maslow was already a 33-year-old father and had two children when the United States entered World War II in 1941. He was thus ineligible for the military. However, the horrors of war inspired a vision of peace in him leading to his groundbreaking psychological studies of self-actualizing. The studies began under the supervision of two mentors, [[anthropology|anthropologist]] [[Ruth Benedict]] and [[Gestalt psychology|Gestalt psychologist]] [[Max Wertheimer]], whom he admired both professionally and personally. They accomplished a lot in both realms. Being such \"wonderful human beings\" as well, they inspired Maslow to take notes about them and their behavior. This would be the basis of his lifelong research and thinking about [[mental health]] and [[human potential]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Abraham Maslow: a biographer's reflections |author=Edward Hoffman |year=2008 |journal=[[Journal of Humanistic Psychology]] |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=439\u2013443 |doi=10.1177/0022167808320534}}</ref> He extended the subject, borrowing ideas from other psychologists and adding new ones, such as the concepts of a [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs|hierarchy of needs]], [[Metamotivation|metaneeds]], [[metamotivation]], [[Self-actualization|self-actualizing]] persons, and [[peak experiences]]. Maslow was a professor at [[Brandeis University]] from 1951 to 1969. He became a resident fellow of the Laughlin Institute in California. In 1967, Maslow had a serious heart attack and knew his time was limited. He considered himself to be a psychological pioneer. He gave future psychologists a push by bringing to light different paths to ponder.<ref>Thoreau, H. (1962). Thoreau: Walden and other writings. New York: Bantam Books. (Original work published 1854)</ref> He built the framework that later allowed other psychologists to conduct more comprehensive studies. Maslow believed that leadership should be non-intervening. Consistent with this approach, he rejected a nomination in 1963 to be the president of the Association for [[Humanistic Psychology]] because he felt that the organization should develop an intellectual movement without a leader.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Miles Vich |year=2008 |title=Maslow's leadership legacy |journal=[[Journal of Humanistic Psychology]] |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=444\u2013445 |doi=10.1177/0022167808320540}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nWhile jogging, Maslow suffered a severe [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] and died on June 8, 1970, at the age of 62 in [[Menlo Park, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muskingum.edu/~psych/psycweb/history/maslow.htm|title=Psychology History|work=muskingum.edu|accessdate=2015-12-20|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220204237/http://www.muskingum.edu/~psych/psycweb/history/maslow.htm|archivedate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |title=Dr. Abraham Maslow, Founder Of Humanistic Psychology, Dies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/10/archives/dr-abraham-maslow-founder-of-humanistic-psychology-dies.html |quote=Dr. Abraham Maslow, professor of psychology at Brandeis University in Waltham, Mass., and founder of what has come to be known as humanistic psychology, died of a heart attack. He was 62 years old. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 10, 1970 |accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref>\n\n==Maslow's contributions==\n\n===Humanistic psychology===\nMaslow's thinking was original. Most psychologists before him had been concerned with the abnormal and the ill. He urged people to acknowledge their basic needs before addressing higher needs and ultimately self-actualization. He wanted to know what constituted positive mental health. [[Humanistic psychology]] gave rise to several different therapies, all guided by the idea that people possess the inner resources for growth and healing and that the point of therapy is to help remove obstacles to individuals' achieving them. The most famous of these was [[client-centered therapy]] developed by [[Carl Rogers]].\n\nThe basic principles behind humanistic psychology are simple:\n\n# Someone's present functioning is their most significant aspect. As a result, humanists emphasize the here and now instead of examining the past or attempting to predict the future.\n# To be mentally healthy, individuals must take personal responsibility for their actions, regardless of whether the actions are positive or negative.\n# Each person, simply by being, is inherently worthy. While any given action may be negative, these actions do not cancel out the value of a person.\n# The ultimate goal of living is to attain personal growth and understanding. Only through constant self-improvement and self-understanding can an individual ever be truly happy.<ref name=\"Humanistic Psychology\">{{cite web|title=Humanistic Psychology |url=http://www.abraham-maslow.com/m_motivation/Humanistic_Psychology.asp |accessdate=21 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824115841/http://www.abraham-maslow.com/m_motivation/Humanistic_Psychology.asp |archivedate=24 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHumanistic psychology theory suits people who see the positive side of humanity and believe in free will. This theory clearly contrasts with Freud's theory of biological determinism. Another significant strength is that humanistic psychology theory is compatible with other schools of thought. Maslow's Hierarchy is also applicable to other topics, such as finance, economics, or even in history or criminology. Humanist psychology, also coined ''positive psychology'', is criticized for its lack of empirical validation and therefore its lack of usefulness in treating specific problems. It may also fail to help or diagnose people who have severe mental disorders.<ref name=\"Humanistic Psychology\"/> [[Humanistic psychologist]]s believe that every person has a strong desire to realize their full potential, to reach a level of \"[[self-actualization]]\". The main point of that new movement, that reached its peak in 1960s, was to emphasize the positive potential of human beings.<ref>Schacter, Daniel L. \"Psychology\"</ref> Maslow positioned his work as a vital complement to that of Freud:\n{{quote|It is as if Freud supplied us the sick half of psychology and we must now fill it out with the healthy half.<ref>Toward a psychology of being, 1968</ref>}}\nHowever, Maslow was highly critical of Freud, since humanistic psychologists did not recognize spirituality as a navigation for our behaviours.<ref>The Personal Meaning of Social Values in the Work of Abraham Maslow\nby John H. Morgan\nInterpersona : An International Journal on Personal Relationships, ISSN 1981-6472, 06/2012, Volume 6, Issue 1, pp. 75 - 93</ref>\n\nTo prove that humans are not blindly reacting to situations, but trying to accomplish something greater, Maslow studied mentally healthy individuals instead of people with serious psychological issues. He focused on self-actualizing people. Self-actualizing people indicate a ''coherent personality syndrome'' and represent optimal psychological health and functioning.<ref>Michael Daniels, [https://doi.org/10.1007%2FBF02684455 \"The Development of the Concept of Selfactualization in the writings of Abraham Maslow\"], \"University of Toronto Libraries\" {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThis informed his theory that a person enjoys \"[[peak experience]]s\", high points in life when the individual is in harmony with himself and his surroundings. In Maslow's view, self-actualized people can have many peak experiences throughout a day while others have those experiences less frequently.<ref>[[#Berger|Berger (1983)]], p. 43.</ref> He believed that psychedelic drugs like [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]] and [[Psilocybin]] can produce peak experiences in the right people under the right circumstances.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Religions, Values, and Peak Experiences|last=Maslow|first=Abraham H.|publisher=Ohio State University Press|year=1964|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n===Peak and plateau experiences===\nBeyond the routine of needs fulfillment, Maslow envisioned moments of extraordinary experience, known as [[Peak experiences]], which are profound moments of love, understanding, happiness, or rapture, during which a person feels more whole, alive, self-sufficient and yet a part of the world, more aware of truth, justice, harmony, goodness, and so on. Self-actualizing people are more likely to have peak experiences. In other words, these \"peak experiences\" or states of flow are the reflections of the realization of one's human potential and represent the height of personality development.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schacter|first=Daniel|title=Psychology Second Edition|year=2009|page=487}}</ref>\n\nIn later writings Maslow moved to a more inclusive model that allowed for, in addition to intense peak experiences, longer-lasting periods of serene Being-cognition that he termed [[Peak experience#Plateau experience|''plateau experiences'']].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Krippner | first1 = Stanley | year = 1972 | title = The plateau experience: A. H. Maslow and others | url = https://www.academia.edu/27103672 | journal = The Journal of Transpersonal Psychology | volume = 4 | issue = 2| pages = 107\u2013120 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Gruel | first1 = Nicole | year = 2015 | title = The plateau experience: an exploration of its origins, characteristics, and potential | url = http://atpweb.org/jtparchive/trps-47-15-01-44.pdf | format = PDF | journal = The Journal of Transpersonal Psychology | volume = 47 | issue = 1| pages = 44\u201363 }}</ref> He borrowed this term from the Indian scientist and yoga praticioner, U. A. Asrani, with whom he corresponded.<ref>Gruel (2015), p. 50.</ref>\n\n===B-values===\nIn studying accounts of peak experiences, Maslow identified a manner of thought he called \"Being-cognition\" (or \"B-cognition\"), which is holistic and accepting, as opposed to the evaluative \"Deficiency-cognition\" (or \"D-cognition\"), and values he called \"Being-values\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Maslow|first=Abraham|title=The Farther Reaches of Human Nature|year=1993|publisher=Arkana|isbn=978-0140194708|page=128}}</ref> He listed the B-values as:\n* Truth (honesty; reality; nakedness; simplicity; richness; oughtness; beauty; pure, clean and unadulterated; completeness; essentiality).\n* Goodness (rightness; desirability; oughtness; justice; benevolence; honesty);\n* Beauty (rightness; form; aliveness; simplicity; richness; wholeness; perfection; completion; uniqueness; honesty);\n* Wholeness (unity; integration; tendency to one-ness; interconnectedness; simplicity; organization; structure; dichotomy-transcendence; order);\n* Aliveness (process; non-deadness; spontaneity; self-regulation; full-functioning);\n* Uniqueness (idiosyncrasy; individuality; non-comparability; novelty);\n* Perfection (necessity; just-right-ness; just-so-ness; inevitability; suitability; justice; completeness; \"oughtness\");\n* Completion (ending; finality; justice; \"it's finished\"; fulfillment; finis and telos; destiny; fate);\n* Justice (fairness; orderliness; lawfulness; \"oughtness\");\n* Simplicity (honesty; nakedness; essentiality; abstract, essential, skeletal structure);\n* Richness (differentiation, complexity; intricacy);\n* Effortlessness (ease; lack of strain, striving or difficulty; grace; perfect, beautiful functioning);\n* Playfulness (fun; joy; amusement; gaiety; humor; exuberance; effortlessness);\n* Self-sufficiency (autonomy; independence; not-needing-other-than-itself-in-order-to-be-itself; self-determining; environment-transcendence; separateness; living by its own laws).\n\n===Hierarchy of needs===\n[[File:Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs.svg|thumb|right|450px|An interpretation of Maslow's hierarchy of needs, represented as a pyramid, with the more basic needs at the bottom<ref name=\"abraham-maslow\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.abraham-maslow.com/m_motivation/Hierarchy_of_Needs.asp |title=Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs |access-date=2011-09-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907194523/http://www.abraham-maslow.com/m_motivation/Hierarchy_of_Needs.asp |archive-date=2011-09-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>]]\n{{main|Maslow's hierarchy of needs}}\nMaslow described human needs as ordered in a prepotent hierarchy\u2014a pressing need would need to be mostly satisfied before someone would give their attention to the next highest need. None of his published works included a visual representation of the hierarchy. The pyramidal diagram illustrating the Maslow needs hierarchy may have been created by a psychology textbook publisher as an illustrative device. This now iconic pyramid frequently depicts the spectrum of human needs, both physical and psychological, as accompaniment to articles describing Maslow's needs theory and may give the impression that the Hierarchy of Needs is a fixed and rigid sequence of progression. Yet, starting with the first publication of his theory in 1943, Maslow described human needs as being relatively fluid\u2014with many needs being present in a person simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Maslow | first1 = A. H. | title = A theory of human motivation | doi = 10.1037/h0054346 | journal = Psychological Review | volume = 50 | issue = 4 | pages = 370\u2013396 | year = 1943 | pmid =  | pmc = | citeseerx = 10.1.1.334.7586 }}</ref>\n\nThe hierarchy of human needs model suggests that human needs will only be fulfilled one level at a time.<ref>Business Volume 1</ref>\n\nAccording to Maslow's theory, when a human being ascends the levels of the hierarchy having fulfilled the needs in the hierarchy, one may eventually achieve self-actualization. Late in life, Maslow came to conclude that self-actualization was not an automatic outcome of satisfying the other human needs <ref>Frick, W. B. (1989). Interview with Dr. Abraham Maslow. In Humanistic psychology: Conversations with Abraham Maslow, Gardner Murphy, Carl Rogers (pp. 19-50). Bristol, IN: Wyndham Hall Press. (Original work published 1971)</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Maslow | first1 = A. H. | title = A Theory of Metamotivation : The Biological Rooting of the Value-Life | doi = 10.1177/002216786700700201 | journal = Journal of Humanistic Psychology | volume = 7 | issue = 2 | pages = 93\u2013126 | year = 1967 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>\n\nHuman needs as identified by Maslow:\n\n* At the bottom of the hierarchy are the \"Basic needs or Physiological needs\" of a human being: food, water, sleep, sex, homeostasis, and excretion. \n* The next level is \"Safety Needs: Security, Order, and Stability\". These two steps are important to the physical survival of the person. Once individuals have basic nutrition, shelter and safety, they attempt to accomplish more.\n* The third level of need is \"Love and Belonging\", which are psychological needs; when individuals have taken care of themselves physically, they are ready to share themselves with others, such as with family and friends.\n* The fourth level is achieved when individuals feel comfortable with what they have accomplished. This is the \"Esteem\" level, the need to be competent and recognized, such as through status and level of success.\n* Then there is the \"Cognitive\" level, where individuals intellectually stimulate themselves and explore.\n* After that is the \"Aesthetic\" level, which is the need for harmony, order and beauty.<ref>Carlson, N.R., et al. (2007). Psychology: The Science of Behaviour \u2013 4th Canadian ed. Toronto, ON: Pearson Education Canada.</ref>\n* At the top of the pyramid, \"Need for Self-actualization\" occurs when individuals reach a state of harmony and understanding because they are engaged in achieving their full potential.<ref>The Developing Person through the Life Span, (1983) pg. 44</ref> Once a person has reached the self-actualization state they focus on themselves and try to build their own image. They may look at this in terms of feelings such as self-confidence or by accomplishing a set goal.<ref name=\"Boeree\"/>\n\nThe first four levels are known as ''Deficit needs'' or ''D-needs''. This means that if you do not have enough of one of those four needs, you will have the feeling that you need to get it. But when you do get them, then you feel content. These needs alone are not motivating.<ref name=\"Boeree\"/>\n\nMaslow wrote that there are certain conditions that must be fulfilled in order for the basic needs to be satisfied. For example, freedom of speech, freedom to express oneself, and freedom to seek new information<ref>A Theory of Human Motivation</ref> are a few of the prerequisites. Any blockages of these freedoms could prevent the satisfaction of the basic needs.\n\nMaslow's Hierarchy is used in higher education for advising students and student retention<ref>Brookman, David M. \"Maslow's Hierarchy and Student Retention\". NACADA Journal, v9 n1 p69-74. Spring 1989.</ref> as well as a key concept in student development.<ref>Villa, R., Thousand, J., Stainback, W. & Stainback, S. [http://www.normemma.com/articles/armaslow.htm \"Restructuring for Caring & Effective Education\"].  Baltimore: Paul Brookes, 1992. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106011155/http://www.normemma.com/articles/armaslow.htm |date=November 6, 2012 }}</ref> Maslow's Hierarchy has been subject to internet memes over the past few years, specifically looking at the modern integration of technology in our lives and humorously suggesting that Wi-Fi was among the most basic of human needs.<ref name=Akufu>{{cite web|title=Maslow's Updated Hierarchy of Needs|url=http://weknowmemes.com/2013/08/maslows-hierarchy-of-needs-updated/|date=2013-08-20}}</ref>\n\n===Self-actualization===\n\nMaslow defined [[Self-actualization]] as achieving the fullest use of one's talents and interests\u2014the need \"to become everything that one is capable of becoming.\"<ref>Michael R. Hagerty, \"Testing Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs: National Quality-of-Life Across Time,\" Social Indicators Research 46(xx), 1999, 250.</ref>  As implied by its name, self-actualization is highly individualistic and reflects Maslow's premise that the self is \"sovereign and inviolable\" and entitled to \"his or her own tastes, opinions, values, etc.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Aron | first1 = Adrianne | year = 1977 | title = Maslow's Other Child | url = | journal = Journal of Humanistic Psychology | volume = 17 | issue = 2| page = 13 }}</ref>  Indeed, some have characterized self-actualization as \"healthy narcissism.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pauchant | first1 = Thierry | last2 = Dumas | first2 = Collette A. | year = 1991 | title = Abraham Maslow and Heinz Kohut: A Comparison | url = | journal = Journal of Humanistic Psychology | volume = 31 | issue = 2| page = 58 | doi = 10.1177/0022167891312005 }}</ref>\n\n===Qualities of self-actualizing people===\nHe realized that all the individuals he studied had similar personality traits. All were \"reality centered,\" able to differentiate what was fraudulent from what was genuine. They were also \"problem centered,\" meaning that they treated life's difficulties as problems that demanded solutions. These individuals also were comfortable being alone and had healthy personal relationships. They had only a few close friends and family rather than a large number of shallow relationships.<ref name=\"ship\">{{cite web|url=http://webspace.ship.edu/cgboer/maslow.html|title=ABRAHAM MASLOW|author=C. George Boeree|accessdate=2009-10-08| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091024142938/http://webspace.ship.edu/cgboer/maslow.html| archivedate= 24 October 2009| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nSelf-actualizing people tend to focus on problems outside themselves; have a clear sense of what is true and what is false; are spontaneous and creative; and are not bound too strictly by social conventions.\n\nMaslow noticed that self-actualized individuals had a better insight of reality, deeply accepted themselves, others and the world, and also had faced many problems and were known to be impulsive people. These self-actualized individuals were very independent and private when it came to their environment and culture, especially their very own individual development on \"potentialities and inner resources\".<ref>{{cite journal |author=Richard L. Schott |year=1992 |title=Abraham Maslow, humanistic psychology, and organization leadership: a Jungian perspective |journal=[[Journal of Humanistic Psychology]] |volume=32 |pages=106\u2013120 |doi=10.1177/0022167892321008}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Maslow, self-actualizing people share the following qualities:\n* Truth: honest, reality, beauty, pure, clean and unadulterated completeness\n* Goodness: rightness, desirability, uprightness, benevolence, honesty\n* Beauty: rightness, form, aliveness, simplicity, richness, wholeness, perfection, completion,\n* Wholeness: unity, integration, tendency to oneness, interconnectedness, simplicity, organization, structure, order, not dissociated, synergy\n* Dichotomy: transcendence, acceptance, resolution, integration, polarities, opposites, contradictions\n* Aliveness: process, not-deadness, spontaneity, self-regulation, full-functioning\n* Uniqueness: idiosyncrasy, individuality, non comparability, novelty\n* Perfection: nothing superfluous, nothing lacking, everything in its right place, just-rightness, suitability, justice\n* Necessity: inevitability: it must be just that way, not changed in any slightest way\n* Completion: ending, justice, fulfillment\n* Justice: fairness, suitability,  disinterestedness, non partiality,\n* Order: lawfulness, rightness, perfectly arranged\n* Simplicity: nakedness, abstract, essential skeletal, bluntness\n* Richness: differentiation, complexity, intricacy, totality\n* Effortlessness: ease; lack of strain, striving, or difficulty\n* Playfulness: fun, joy, amusement\n* Self-sufficiency: autonomy, independence, self-determining.<ref name=\"Metaneeds\">{{cite web|url=http://webspace.ship.edu/cgboer/maslow.html |title=Metaneeds and metapathologies |accessdate=2010-04-12}}</ref>\n\nMaslow based his theory partially on his own assumptions about human potential and partially on his case studies of historical figures whom he believed to be self-actualized, including [[Albert Einstein]] and [[Henry David Thoreau]].<ref>Carlson, N. R. (19992000). Memory. Psychology: the science of behaviour (Canandian ed., p. 461). Scarborough, Ont.: Allyn and Bacon Canada.</ref> Consequently, Maslow argued, the way in which essential needs are fulfilled is just as important as the needs themselves. Together, these define the human experience. To the extent a person finds cooperative social fulfillment, he establishes meaningful relationships with other people and the larger world. In other words, he  establishes meaningful connections to an external reality\u2014an essential component of self-actualization. In contrast, to the extent that vital needs find selfish and competitive fulfillment, a person acquires hostile emotions and limited external relationships\u2014his awareness remains internal and limited.\n\n===Metamotivation===\nMaslow used the term [[metamotivation]] to describe self-actualized people who are driven by innate forces beyond their basic needs, so that they may explore and reach their full human potential.<ref>[[#Goble|Goble (1970)]]</ref>\n\n===Methodology===\nMaslow based his study on the writings of other psychologists, [[Albert Einstein]] and people he knew who [he felt] clearly met the standard of self-actualization.<ref>{{cite web|author=McLeod, S. A|year=2007|title= Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs|url=http://www.simplypsychology.org/maslow.html|publisher=Simplypsychology.org|accessdate=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nMaslow used Einstein's writings and accomplishments to exemplify the characteristics of the self-actualized person. But [[Ruth Benedict]] and [[Max Wertheimer]] were also Maslow's models of self-actualization.  In this case, from a scientific perspective there are numerous problems with this particular approach.  First, it could be argued that biographical analysis as a method is extremely subjective as it is based entirely on the opinion of the researcher.  Personal opinion is always prone to bias, which reduces the validity of any data obtained.  Therefore, Maslow's operational definition of Self-actualization must not be blindly accepted as scientific fact.<ref>{{cite web|author=McLeod, S. A|year=2007|title= Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs|url=http://www.simplypsychology.org/maslow.html|publisher=Simplypsychology.org|accessdate=2012-10-21}}</ref>\n\n===Transpersonal psychology===\nDuring the 1960s Maslow founded with Stanislav Grof, Viktor Frankl, James Fadiman, Anthony Sutich, Miles Vich and Michael Murphy, the school of [[transpersonal psychology]]. Maslow had concluded that humanistic psychology was incapable of explaining all aspects of human experience. He identified various mystical, ecstatic, or spiritual states known as \"[[peak experiences]]\" as experiences beyond self-actualization. Maslow called these experiences \"a fourth force in psychology\", which he named transpersonal psychology. Transpersonal psychology was concerned with the \"empirical, scientific study of, and responsible implementation of the finding relevant to, becoming, mystical, ecstatic, and spiritual states\" (Olson & Hergenhahn, 2011).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMaslow published in 1962 a collection of papers on this theme, which developed into his 1968 book ''Toward a Psychology of Being''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|author1=Matthew H. Olson|author2=B. R. Hergenhahn|title=An Introduction to Theories of Personality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ISJ6QgAACAAJ|year=2011|publisher=Prentice Hall/Pearson|isbn=978-0-205-79878-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Maslow2013\">{{cite book|author=Abraham H. Maslow|title=Toward a Psychology of Being|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jcKbDAAAQBAJ|date=18 July 2013|orig-year=first published 1968|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-62793-274-5}}</ref> In this book Maslow stresses the importance of transpersonal psychology to human beings, writing: \"without the transpersonal, we get sick, violent, and nihilistic, or else hopeless and apathetic\" (Olson & Hergenhahn, 2011).<ref name=\":0\" /> Human beings, he came to believe, need something bigger than themselves that they are connected to in a naturalistic sense, but not in a religious sense: Maslow himself was an [[Atheism|atheist]]<ref name=\"Hamer2005\">{{cite book|author=Dean H. Hamer|title=The God Gene: How Faith Is Hardwired into Our Genes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKRphq7s7x0C&pg=PA19|date=27 September 2005|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-27693-3|pages=19\u2013}}</ref> and found it difficult to accept religious experience as valid unless placed in a [[Positivism|positivistic]] framework.<ref name=\"Hoffman, E. 1999\">{{cite book|author=Edward Hoffman|title=The Right to Be Human: A Biography of Abraham Maslow|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=USSePwAACAAJ|date=1 March 1994|publisher=Four Worlds Press|isbn=978-0-9637902-3-1}}</ref> In fact, Maslow's position on God and religion was quite complex. While he rejected organized religion and its beliefs, he wrote extensively on the human being's need for the sacred and spoke of God in more philosophical terms, as beauty, truth and goodness, or as a force or a principle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.awaken.com/2013/01/abraham-maslow-and-spirituality/|title=Abraham Maslow and Spirituality {{!}} Awaken|website=www.awaken.com|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oaks.nvg.org/maslow-rvl.html|title=Abraham Maslow on Religion, Values of Self-actualisers, and Peak Experiences \u2013 The Gold Scales|website=oaks.nvg.org|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref>\n\nAwareness of transpersonal psychology became widespread within psychology, and the ''Journal of Transpersonal Psychology'' was founded in 1969, a year after Abraham Maslow became the president of the American Psychological Association. In the United States, transpersonal psychology encouraged recognition for [[non-western]] psychologies, philosophies, and religions, and promoted understanding of \"higher states of consciousness\", for instance through intense [[meditation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thepositiveencourager.global/abraham-maslows-approach-to-doing-positive-work/|title=M is for Abraham Maslow: A Founder of Humanistic Psychology|date=2014-12-19|newspaper=The Positive Encourager|access-date=2016-12-13}}</ref> Transpersonal psychology has been applied in many areas, including [[transpersonal business studies]].\n\n===Positive psychology===\nMaslow called his work [[positive psychology]].<ref>''Two Thoughts on Abraham Maslow'' by David L Rennie</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Two Thoughts on Abraham Maslow - David Rennie | publisher=Journal of Humanistic Psychology | date= }}</ref> His work has influenced since 1968 the development of [[Positive Psychotherapy]], a transcultural, humanistic based psychodynamic psychotherapy method used in mental health and psychosomatic treatment founded by [[Nossrat Peseschkian]].<ref>''Positive Psychotherapie'' by Nossrat Peseschkian. Fischer: 1977. ''Positive Psychotherapy'' by Nossrat Peseschkian. Springer: 1987.</ref> Since 1999 Maslows work enjoyed a revival of interest and influence among leaders of the [[positive psychology]] movement such as [[Martin Seligman]]. This movement focuses only on a higher human nature.<ref>''Character Strengths and Virtues: A Handbook and Classification'' by Christopher Peterson, Martin E. P. Seligman. Oxford University Press: 2004 {{ISBN|0-19-516701-5}} pg 62</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QqPiF1C7cy4C&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=maslow+seligmann#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Character Strengths and Virtues: A Handbook and Classification - Christopher Peterson, Martin E. P. Seligman - Google Books |accessdate=2012-10-21|isbn=9780195167016 |year=2004 |last1=Peterson |first1=Christopher |last2=Seligman |first2=Martin E. P. |last3=Fox Leadership Professor Of Psychology Martin e p Seligman |first3=Ph.D }}</ref>\nPositive psychology spends its research looking at the positive side of things and how they go right rather than the pessimistic side.<ref>Gilbert, D. (2006). Stumbling on happiness. Toronto, Ontario: Random House.</ref>\n\n=== Psychology of science ===\nIn 1966, Maslow published a pioneering work in the psychology of science ''The Psychology of Science: A Reconnaissance'', the first book ever actually titled \u2018psychology of science\u2019. In this book Maslow proposed a model of \u2018characterologically relative\u2019 science, which he characterized as an ardent opposition to the \u2018\u2018historically, philosophically, sociologically and psychologically na\u0131ve\u2019\u2019 positivistic reluctance to see science \u2018\u2018relative to time, place, and local culture\u2019\u2019.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Psychology of Science: A Reconnaissance|last=Maslow|first=Abraham|publisher=Gateway Editions|year=1969|isbn=|location=South Bend, Indiana|pages=1|via=}}</ref> As Maslow acknowledged, the book was greatly inspired by Thomas Kuhn's ''The Structure of Scientific Revolutions'' (1962), and it offers a psychological reading of Kuhn's famous distinction between \"normal\" and \"revolutionary\" science in the context of his own distinction between \"safety\" and \"growth\" science, put forward as part of a larger program for the psychology of science, outlined already in his 1954 ''magnum opus'' ''Motivation and Personality''. Not only that Maslow offered a psychological reading of Kuhn's categories of \"normal\" and \"revolutionary\" science as an aftermath of Kuhn's ''Structure'', but he also offered a strikingly similar dichotomous structure of science 16 years before the first edition of ''Structure'', in his nowadays little known 1946 paper \"Means-Centering Versus Problem-Centering in Science\" published in the journal ''Philosophy of Science''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ko\u017enjak|first=Boris|date=2017|title=Kuhn Meets Maslow: The Psychology Behind Scientific Revolutions|journal=Journal for General Philosophy of Science|volume=48|issue=2|pages=257\u2013287|doi=10.1007/s10838-016-9352-x}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maslow|first=Abraham|date=1946|title=Problem-centering vs. means-centering in science|journal=Philosophy of Science|volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=326\u2013331 |doi=10.1086/286907|jstor=185213}}</ref>\n\n===Maslow's hammer===\nAbraham Maslow is also known for [[Maslow's hammer]], popularly phrased as \"[[wikt:if all you have is a hammer, everything looks like a nail|if all you have is a hammer, everything looks like a nail]]\"  from his book ''The Psychology of Science'', published in 1966.<ref name=maslow66>\n{{cite book\n | title = The Psychology of Science\n | author = Abraham H. Maslow\n | year = 1966\n | isbn =9780976040231| page = 15\n | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3_40fK8PW6QC&printsec=frontcover#PPT7,M1\n | accessdate = 2015-12-20\n}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nMaslow's ideas have been criticized for their lack of scientific rigor. He was criticized as too soft scientifically by American empiricists.<ref name=\"Hoffman, E. 1999\"/> In 2006, author and former philosophy professor [[Christina Hoff Sommers]] and practicing psychiatrist [[Sally Satel]] asserted that, due to lack of empirical support, Maslow's ideas have fallen out of fashion and are \"no longer taken seriously in the world of academic psychology.\"<ref>[[#Sommers|Sommers & Satel (2006)]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=sVT_i83KAhMC&dq=one+nation+under+therapy&printsec=frontcover&source=bn&hl=en&ei=2jrjS9GiKJPssQPe-JW6DQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=maslow&f=false p. 74 & passim in chapter 2]</ref>\nPositive psychology spends much of its research looking for how things go right rather than the more pessimistic view point, how things go wrong.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Peterson|first= C. |year=2009|title= Positive psychology. |journal = Reclaiming Children and Youth|volume= 18|issue=2|pages= 3\u20137}}</ref>\nFurthermore, the Hierarchy of Needs has been accused of having a cultural bias\u2014mainly reflecting Western values and ideologies. From the perspective of many cultural psychologists, this concept is considered relative to each culture and society and cannot be universally applied.<ref>Keith E Rice,[http://www.integratedsociopsychology.net/hierearchy_of_needs.html \"Hierarchy of Needs\"], ''Integrated Sociopsychology'', 9/12/12 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212143440/http://www.integratedsociopsychology.net/hierearchy_of_needs.html |date=February 12, 2015 }}</ref> However, according to the University of Illinois researchers Ed Diener and Louis Tay,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Diener|first=Ed|last2=Tay|first2=Louis|date=2011|title=Needs and subjective well-being around the world|url=|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume=101 |issue=2|pages=354\u2013365|doi=10.1037/a0023779|pmid=21688922|access-date=}}</ref> who put Maslow's ideas to the test with data collected from 60,865 participants in 123 countries around the world over the period of five years (2005-2010), Maslow was essentially right in that there are universal human needs regardless of cultural differences, although the authors claim to have found certain departures from the order of their fulfillment Maslow described. In particular, while they found&mdash;clearly in accordance with Maslow&mdash;that people tend to achieve basic and safety needs before other needs, as well as that other \"higher needs\" tend to be fulfilled in a certain order, the order in which they are fulfilled apparently does not strongly influence their subjective well-being (SWB). As put by the authors of the study, humans thus\n\n{{Quote|text=can derive 'happiness' from simultaneously working on a number of needs regardless of the fulfillment of other needs. This might be why people in impoverished nations, with only modest control over whether their basic needs are fulfilled, can nevertheless find a measure of well-being through social relationships and other psychological needs over which they have more control.|sign=|source=Diener & Tay (2011), p. 364}}\n\nMaslow, however, would not be surprised by these findings, since he clearly and repeatedly emphasized that the need hierarchy is not a rigid fixed order as it is often presented:\n\n{{Quote|text=We have spoken so far as if this hierarchy were a fixed order, but actually it is not nearly so rigid as we may have implied. It is true that most of the people with whom we have worked have seemed to have these basic needs in about the order that has been indicated. However, there have been a number of exceptions.|sign=|source=Maslow, 'Motivation and Personality' (1970), p. 51}}\n\nMaslow also regarded that the relationship between different human needs and behaviour, being in fact often motivated simultaneously by multiple needs, is not a one-to-one correspondence, i.e., that \"these needs must be understood not to be exclusive or single determiners of certain kinds of behavior\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Motivation and Personalty|last=Maslow|first=Abraham|year=1970|isbn=|location=|pages=55|via=}}</ref>\n\nMaslow's concept of self-actualizing people was united with Piaget's developmental theory to the process of initiation in 1993.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/663726|title=Oliver Kress - A new approach to cognitive development: ontogenesis and the process of initiation|author=Oliver Kress|accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nLater in life, Maslow was concerned with questions such as, \"Why don't more people self-actualize if their basic needs are met?\nHow can we humanistically understand the problem of evil?\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rennie, David |year=2008 |title=Two thoughts on Abraham Maslow|journal= Journal of Humanistic Psychology|volume= 48|issue=4|pages=445\u2013448|doi=10.1177/0022167808320537}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 1961, Maslow and Tony Sutich founded the ''Journal of Humanistic Psychology'', with Miles Vich as editor until 1971.<ref name=\"Greening\">{{cite journal|author=Greening, Tom |year=2008 |title=Abraham Maslow: A Brief Reminiscence|journal= Journal of Humanistic Psychology|volume=48|issue=4 |pages=443\u2013444 |doi=10.1177/0022167808320533 }}</ref> The journal printed its first issue in early 1961 and continues to publish academic papers.<ref name=\"Greening\"/>\n\nMaslow attended the Association for Humanistic Psychology's founding meeting in 1963 where he declined nomination as its president, arguing that the new organization should develop an intellectual movement without a leader which resulted in useful strategy during the field's early years.<ref>Abraham Maslow: A Brief Reminiscence\nJournal of Humanistic Psychology (October 2008), 48 (4), pg. 443-444 \nTom Greening</ref>\n\nIn 1967, Maslow was named [[Humanist of the Year]] by the [[American Humanist Association]].<ref name=AHA>{{cite web|title=Humanists of the Year|url=http://americanhumanist.org/AHA/Humanists_of_the_Year|work=American Humanist Association|accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Writings==\n* \"[http://psychclassics.yorku.ca/Maslow/motivation.htm A Theory of Human Motivation]\" (originally published in ''Psychological Review'', 1943, Vol. 50 #4, pp.&nbsp;370\u2013396).\n* ''[[Motivation and Personality]]'' (1st edition: 1954, 2nd edition: 1970, 3rd edition 1987)\n* ''[[Religions, Values, and Peak Experiences]]'', Columbus, Ohio: [[Ohio State University Press]], 1964.\n* ''[[Eupsychian Management]]'', 1965; republished as ''[[Maslow on Management]]'', 1998\n* ''The Psychology of Science: A Reconnaissance'', New York: [[Harper & Row]], 1966; Chapel Hill: Maurice Bassett, 2002.\n* ''Toward a Psychology of Being'', (1st edition, 1962; 2nd edition, 1968)\n* ''The Farther Reaches of Human Nature'', 1971\n* ''Future Visions: The Unpublished Papers of Abraham Maslow'' by E. L. Hoffman (editor) 1996\n* ''Personality and Growth: A Humanistic Psychologist in the Classroom'', Anna Maria, FL: Maurice Bassett, 2019.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Psychology}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Clayton Alderfer]]\n* [[Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi]]\n* [[Frederick Herzberg]]\n* [[Human Potential Movement]]\n* [[Law of the instrument]]\n* [[Manfred Max-Neef]]\n* [[Rollo May]]\n* [[Organismic theory]]\n* [[Organizational behavior]]\n* [[Positive Disintegration]]\n* [[Post-materialism]]\n* [[Reverence (emotion)|Reverence]]\n* [[Self-esteem]]\n* [[Victor Vroom]]\n* [[Erich Fromm]]\n* [[Humanistic psychology]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Developing Person through the Life Span |last=Berger |first=Kathleen Stassen |year=1983 |ref=Berger}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Third Force: The Psychology of Abraham Maslow |last=Goble |first=F. |publisher=Maurice Bassett Publishing |year=1970 |location=Richmond, CA |ref=Goble}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Goud, N  |year=2008 |title=Abraham maslow: A personal statement. |journal=Journal of Humanistic Psychology |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=448\u2013451 |doi=10.1177/0022167808320535|first1=N. }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Right to be Human: A Biography of Abraham Maslow |url=https://archive.org/details/righttobehuman00edwa |url-access=registration |last=Hoffman |first=Edward |publisher=St. Martin's Press |year=1988 |location=New York |ref=Hoffman}}\n* {{Citation | last =Hoffman | first =E. | title =Abraham Maslow: A Brief Reminiscence. In: Journal of Humanistic Psychology Fall 2008 vol. 48 no. 4 443-444  | year =1999 | place =New York | publisher =McGraw-Hill}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Rennie  | first =David  |year=2008 |title=Two Thoughts on Abraham Maslow. | journal =Journal of Humanistic Psychology  | volume =48  | issue =4  | pages =445\u2013448  |doi=10.1177/0022167808320537}}\n* {{cite book |title=One Nation Under Therapy: How the Helping Culture is Eroding Self-reliance |last2=Satel |first2=Sally |publisher=MacMillan |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-312-30444-7 |ref=Sommers|last1=Sommers |first1=Christina Hoff }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooks=no|about=yes|wikititle=Abraham Maslow}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Cooke | first1 = B | last2 = Mills | first2 = A | last3 = Kelley | first3 = E | year = 2005 | title = Situating Maslow in Cold War America | url = | journal = Group and Organization Management | volume = 30 | issue = 2| pages = 129\u2013152 | doi=10.1177/1059601104273062}}\n* DeCarvalho, Roy Jose (1991) ''The Founders of Humanistic Psychology''. Praeger Publishers\n* Grogan, Jessica (2012) ''Encountering America: Humanistic Psychology, Sixties Culture, and the Shaping of the Modern Self''. Harper Perennial \n* Hoffman, Edward (1999) ''The Right to Be Human''. McGraw-Hill  {{ISBN|0-07-134267-2}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Wahba | first1 = M.A. | last2 = Bridwell | first2 = L. G. | year = 1976 | title = Maslow Reconsidered: A Review of Research on the Need Hierarchy Theory | url = | journal = Organizational Behavior and Human Performance | volume = 15 | issue = 2| pages = 212\u2013240 | doi=10.1016/0030-5073(76)90038-6}}\n* Wilson, Colin (1972) ''New Pathways in Psychology: Maslow and the post-Freudian revolution''. London: Victor Gollancz ({{ISBN|0-575-01355-9}})\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Abraham Maslow}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051203221954/http://www.maslow.org/sub/m_bib.htm Comprehensive bibliography of Maslow's works]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071022173753/http://faculty.vassar.edu/lowry/maslow1.html \"Maslow's Vision of Human Nature\"] adapted from the Editor's Introduction to ''Toward a Psychology of Being'' (3rd ed.)\n* [http://www.panarchy.org/maslow/being.1955.html Excerpts from ''Toward a Psychology of Being'', 2nd ed.]\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Abraham Harold Maslow}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=3653}}\n* [http://www.abrahammaslow.com/podcasts.html Abraham Maslow Audio Collection]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sfmo04EZP3o \"Being Abraham Maslow\". Rare documentary about Abraham Maslow in a conversation with Warren Bennis of the University of Cincinnati from 1968.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151220204237/http://www.muskingum.edu/~psych/psycweb/history/maslow.htm Psychology History-Abraham Maslow, Compiled by Michelle Emrich]\n\n{{APA Presidents}}\n{{Psychology}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maslow, Abraham}}\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century psychologists]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American humanists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:American psychology writers]]\n[[Category:Boys High School (Brooklyn) alumni]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University faculty]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn College faculty]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:History of mental health]]\n[[Category:Humanistic psychologists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American social scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish atheists]]\n[[Category:Motivation theorists]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from Menlo Park, California]]\n[[Category:Positive psychologists]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the American Psychological Association]]\n[[Category:Transpersonal psychologists]]\n[[Category:University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American psychologist}}\n{{pp-pc1}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n|name             = Abraham Maslow\n|image            = Abraham Maslow.jpg\n|birth_name=Abraham Harold Maslow\n|birth_date       = {{birth-date|April 1, 1908}}\n|birth_place      = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|death_date       = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1970|06|08|1908|04|01}}\n|death_place      = [[Menlo Park, California|Menlo Park]], [[California]], U.S.\n|spouse           = {{marriage|Bertha Goodman Maslow|December 31, 1928}}\n|children         = {{hlist|Ann Maslow|Ellen Maslow}}\n|nationality      = American\n|field            = [[Psychology]]\n|work_institution = {{unbulleted list | [[Cornell University]] | [[Brooklyn College]] | [[Brandeis University]]}}\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]]\n|doctoral_advisor = [[Harry Harlow]]\n|influences       = {{hlist | [[Alfred Adler]] | [[Kurt Goldstein]] | [[Henry Murray]]}}\n|influenced       = {{hlist | [[Douglas McGregor]] | [[Roberto Assagioli]]<ref>Assagioli Roberto. ''Act of Will''. New York: Synthesis Center Press, 2010. Print.</ref> | [[Colin Wilson]] | [[Abbie Hoffman]] | [[Wayne Dyer]] | [[Elliot Aronson]]}}\n|known_for        = [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs]]\n}}\n\n'''Abraham Harold Maslow''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|m|\u00e6|z|l|o\u028a}}; April 1, 1908&nbsp;\u2013 June 8, 1970) was an American psychologist who was best known for creating [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs]], a theory of psychological health predicated on fulfilling innate human needs in priority, culminating in self-actualization.<ref name=obit>{{cite news |author= |title=Dr. Abraham Maslow, Founder Of Humanistic Psychology, Dies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/10/archives/dr-abraham-maslow-founder-of-humanistic-psychology-dies.html |quote=Dr. Abraham Maslow, professor of psychology at Brandeis University in Waltham, Mass., and founder of what has come to be known as humanistic psychology, died  of a heart attack. He was 62 years old. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 10, 1970 |accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref> Maslow was a [[psychology]] professor at [[Alliant International University]], [[Brandeis University]], [[Brooklyn College]], [[New School for Social Research]], and [[Columbia University]]. He stressed the importance of focusing on the positive qualities in people, as opposed to treating them as a \"bag of symptoms\".<ref name=hoffman109>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 109.</ref> A ''[[Review of General Psychology]]'' survey, published in 2002, ranked Maslow as the tenth most cited psychologist of the 20th century.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Haggbloom |first=Steven J. |title=The 100 most eminent psychologists of the 20th century |journal=Review of General Psychology |volume=6 |issue=2 |year=2002 |pages=139\u2013152 |doi=10.1037/1089-2680.6.2.139 |url=http://www.apa.org/monitor/julaug02/eminent.aspx |last2=Warnick |first2=Renee |last3=Warnick |first3=Jason E. |last4=Jones |first4=Vinessa K. |last5=Yarbrough |first5=Gary L. |last6=Russell |first6=Tenea M. |last7=Borecky |first7=Chris M. |last8=McGahhey |first8=Reagan |last9=Powell |first9=John L., III| displayauthors = 8 |citeseerx=10.1.1.586.1913 }}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Youth===\nBorn in 1908 and raised in [[Brooklyn, New York]], Maslow was the oldest of seven children. His parents were first generation [[Jewish]] immigrants from [[Kiev]], then part of the [[Russian Empire]] (now [[Ukraine]]), who fled from Czarist persecution in the early 20th century.<ref name=\"Boeree\">{{cite web|author=Boeree, C.|year=2006|url=http://webspace.ship.edu/cgboer/maslow.html/|title=Abraham Maslow|publisher=Webspace.ship.edu|accessdate=2012-10-21}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=ZCvrS9DjE68C&pg=PT322&dq=Abraham+Maslow+Kiev&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi8g_XawOXRAhVoIcAKHS7dC8cQ6AEIRTAI#v=onepage&q=Abraham%20Maslow%20Kiev&f=false Dreaming To Some Purpose] by [[Colin Wilson]], [[Arrow Books]], {{ISBN|0099471477}}, 2004</ref> They had decided to live in New York City and in a multiethnic, working-class neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web|title=Maslow, Abraham H.|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/article-1G2-3456300032/maslow-abraham-h.html}}</ref> His parents were poor and not intellectually focused, but they valued education. He had various encounters with anti-Semitic gangs who would chase and throw rocks at him.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 9.</ref> Maslow and other young people with his background were struggling to overcome such acts of racism and ethnic prejudice in the attempt to establish an idealistic world based on widespread education and economic justice.<ref>Journal of Humanistic Psychology (October 2008), 48 (4), pg. 439-443</ref> The tension outside his home was also felt within it, as he rarely got along with his mother, and eventually developed a strong revulsion towards her. He is quoted as saying, \"What I had reacted to was not only her physical appearance, but also her values and world view, her stinginess, her total selfishness, her lack of love for anyone else in the world &nbsp;\u2013 even her own husband and children &nbsp;\u2013 her narcissism, her Negro prejudice, her exploitation of everyone, her assumption that anyone was wrong who disagreed with her, her lack of friends, her sloppiness and dirtiness...\". He also grew up with few friends other than his cousin Will, and as a result \"...[He] grew up in libraries and among books.\"<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 11.</ref> It was here that he developed his love for reading and learning. He went to [[Boys High School (Brooklyn)|Boys High School]], one of the top high schools in Brooklyn.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 12</ref> Here, he served as the officer to many academic clubs, and became editor of the Latin Magazine. He also edited ''Principia,'' the school's Physics paper, for a year.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 13.</ref> He developed other strengths as well: {{quote|As a young boy, Maslow believed physical strength to be the single most defining characteristic of a true male; hence, he exercised often and took up weight lifting in hopes of being transformed into a more muscular, tough-looking guy, however, he was unable to achieve this due to his humble-looking and chaste figure as well as his studiousness.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Nicholson|first=Ian|title=Giving up maleness: Abraham Maslow, masculinity, and the boundaries of psychology|journal=History of Psychology|date=February 2001|volume=4|issue=1|pages=79\u201391|doi=10.1037/1093-4510.4.1.79|id={{ProQuest|614416838}}}}{{Dead link|date=January 2013}}</ref>}}\n\n===College and university===\nMaslow attended the [[City College of New York]] after high school. In 1926 he began taking legal studies classes at night in addition to his undergraduate course load. He hated it and almost immediately dropped out. In 1927 he transferred to Cornell, but he left after just one semester due to poor grades and high costs.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 30.</ref> He later graduated from City College and went to graduate school at the [[University of Wisconsin]] to study [[psychology]]. In 1928, he married his first cousin Bertha, who was still in high school at the time. The pair had met in Brooklyn years earlier.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 40.</ref> Maslow's psychology training at UW was decidedly experimental-behaviorist.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 39.</ref> At Wisconsin he pursued a line of research which included investigating [[primate]] [[Dominance (ethology)|dominance]] behavior and [[Human sexuality|sexuality]]. Maslow's early experience with behaviorism would leave him with a strong [[positivism|positivist]] mindset.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite journal|author=Hoffman, E|year=2008|title=Abraham Maslow: A Biographer's Reflection|journal=Journal of Humanistic Psychology|volume= 48|issue=4|pages=439\u2013443|doi=10.1177/0022167808320534}}</ref> Upon the recommendation of Professor Hulsey Cason, Maslow wrote his master's thesis on \"learning, retention, and reproduction of verbal material\".<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 44.</ref> Maslow regarded the research as embarrassingly trivial, but he completed his thesis the summer of 1931 and was awarded his master's degree in psychology. He was so ashamed of the thesis that he removed it from the psychology library and tore out its catalog listing.<ref>[[#Hoffman|Hoffmann (1988)]], p. 45.</ref> However, Professor Cason admired the research enough to urge Maslow to submit it for publication. Maslow's thesis was published as two articles in 1934.\n\n===Academic career===\nHe continued his research at [[Columbia University]] on similar themes. There he found another mentor in [[Alfred Adler]], one of [[Sigmund Freud]]'s early colleagues. From 1937 to 1951, Maslow was on the faculty of [[Brooklyn College]]. His family life and his experiences influenced his psychological ideas. After [[World War II]], Maslow began to question the way psychologists had come to their conclusions, and although he did not completely disagree, he had his own ideas on how to understand the human mind.<ref>[[#Berger|Berger (1983)]], p. 42.</ref> He called his new discipline [[humanistic psychology]]. Maslow was already a 33-year-old father and had two children when the United States entered World War II in 1941. He was thus ineligible for the military. However, the horrors of war inspired a vision of peace in him leading to his groundbreaking psychological studies of self-actualizing. The studies began under the supervision of two mentors, [[anthropology|anthropologist]] [[Ruth Benedict]] and [[Gestalt psychology|Gestalt psychologist]] [[Max Wertheimer]], whom he admired both professionally and personally. They accomplished a lot in both realms. Being such \"wonderful human beings\" as well, they inspired Maslow to take notes about them and their behavior. This would be the basis of his lifelong research and thinking about [[mental health]] and [[human potential]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Abraham Maslow: a biographer's reflections |author=Edward Hoffman |year=2008 |journal=[[Journal of Humanistic Psychology]] |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=439\u2013443 |doi=10.1177/0022167808320534}}</ref> He extended the subject, borrowing ideas from other psychologists and adding new ones, such as the concepts of a [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs|hierarchy of needs]], [[Metamotivation|metaneeds]], [[metamotivation]], [[Self-actualization|self-actualizing]] persons, and [[peak experiences]]. Maslow was a professor at [[Brandeis University]] from 1951 to 1969. He became a resident fellow of the Laughlin Institute in California. In 1967, Maslow had a serious heart attack and knew his time was limited. He considered himself to be a psychological pioneer. He gave future psychologists a push by bringing to light different paths to ponder.<ref>Thoreau, H. (1962). Thoreau: Walden and other writings. New York: Bantam Books. (Original work published 1854)</ref> He built the framework that later allowed other psychologists to conduct more comprehensive studies. Maslow believed that leadership should be non-intervening. Consistent with this approach, he rejected a nomination in 1963 to be the president of the Association for [[Humanistic Psychology]] because he felt that the organization should develop an intellectual movement without a leader.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Miles Vich |year=2008 |title=Maslow's leadership legacy |journal=[[Journal of Humanistic Psychology]] |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=444\u2013445 |doi=10.1177/0022167808320540}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nWhile jogging, Maslow suffered a severe [[Myocardial infarction|heart attack]] and died on June 8, 1970, at the age of 62 in [[Menlo Park, California]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muskingum.edu/~psych/psycweb/history/maslow.htm|title=Psychology History|work=muskingum.edu|accessdate=2015-12-20|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220204237/http://www.muskingum.edu/~psych/psycweb/history/maslow.htm|archivedate=2015-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author= |title=Dr. Abraham Maslow, Founder Of Humanistic Psychology, Dies |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/06/10/archives/dr-abraham-maslow-founder-of-humanistic-psychology-dies.html |quote=Dr. Abraham Maslow, professor of psychology at Brandeis University in Waltham, Mass., and founder of what has come to be known as humanistic psychology, died of a heart attack. He was 62 years old. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=June 10, 1970 |accessdate=2010-09-26}}</ref>\n\n==Maslow's contributions==\n\n===Humanistic psychology===\nMaslow's thinking was original. Most psychologists before him had been concerned with the abnormal and the ill. He urged people to acknowledge their basic needs before addressing higher needs and ultimately self-actualization. He wanted to know what constituted positive mental health. [[Humanistic psychology]] gave rise to several different therapies, all guided by the idea that people possess the inner resources for growth and healing and that the point of therapy is to help remove obstacles to individuals' achieving them. The most famous of these was [[client-centered therapy]] developed by [[Carl Rogers]].\n\nThe basic principles behind humanistic psychology are simple:\n\n# Someone's present functioning is their most significant aspect. As a result, humanists emphasize the here and now instead of examining the past or attempting to predict the future.\n# To be mentally healthy, individuals must take personal responsibility for their actions, regardless of whether the actions are positive or negative.\n# Each person, simply by being, is inherently worthy. While any given action may be negative, these actions do not cancel out the value of a person.\n# The ultimate goal of living is to attain personal growth and understanding. Only through constant self-improvement and self-understanding can an individual ever be truly happy.<ref name=\"Humanistic Psychology\">{{cite web|title=Humanistic Psychology |url=http://www.abraham-maslow.com/m_motivation/Humanistic_Psychology.asp |accessdate=21 August 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120824115841/http://www.abraham-maslow.com/m_motivation/Humanistic_Psychology.asp |archivedate=24 August 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHumanistic psychology theory suits people who see the positive side of humanity and believe in free will. This theory clearly contrasts with Freud's theory of biological determinism. Another significant strength is that humanistic psychology theory is compatible with other schools of thought. Maslow's Hierarchy is also applicable to other topics, such as finance, economics, or even in history or criminology. Humanist psychology, also coined ''positive psychology'', is criticized for its lack of empirical validation and therefore its lack of usefulness in treating specific problems. It may also fail to help or diagnose people who have severe mental disorders.<ref name=\"Humanistic Psychology\"/> [[Humanistic psychologist]]s believe that every person has a strong desire to realize their full potential, to reach a level of \"[[self-actualization]]\". The main point of that new movement, that reached its peak in 1960s, was to emphasize the positive potential of human beings.<ref>Schacter, Daniel L. \"Psychology\"</ref> Maslow positioned his work as a vital complement to that of Freud:\n{{quote|It is as if Freud supplied us the sick half of psychology and we must now fill it out with the healthy half.<ref>Toward a psychology of being, 1968</ref>}}\nHowever, Maslow was highly critical of Freud, since humanistic psychologists did not recognize spirituality as a navigation for our behaviours.<ref>The Personal Meaning of Social Values in the Work of Abraham Maslow\nby John H. Morgan\nInterpersona : An International Journal on Personal Relationships, ISSN 1981-6472, 06/2012, Volume 6, Issue 1, pp. 75 - 93</ref>\n\nTo prove that humans are not blindly reacting to situations, but trying to accomplish something greater, Maslow studied mentally healthy individuals instead of people with serious psychological issues. He focused on self-actualizing people. Self-actualizing people indicate a ''coherent personality syndrome'' and represent optimal psychological health and functioning.<ref>Michael Daniels, [https://doi.org/10.1007%2FBF02684455 \"The Development of the Concept of Selfactualization in the writings of Abraham Maslow\"], \"University of Toronto Libraries\" {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\nThis informed his theory that a person enjoys \"[[peak experience]]s\", high points in life when the individual is in harmony with himself and his surroundings. In Maslow's view, self-actualized people can have many peak experiences throughout a day while others have those experiences less frequently.<ref>[[#Berger|Berger (1983)]], p. 43.</ref> He believed that psychedelic drugs like [[Lysergic acid diethylamide|LSD]] and [[Psilocybin]] can produce peak experiences in the right people under the right circumstances.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Religions, Values, and Peak Experiences|last=Maslow|first=Abraham H.|publisher=Ohio State University Press|year=1964|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n===Peak and plateau experiences===\nBeyond the routine of needs fulfillment, Maslow envisioned moments of extraordinary experience, known as [[Peak experiences]], which are profound moments of love, understanding, happiness, or rapture, during which a person feels more whole, alive, self-sufficient and yet a part of the world, more aware of truth, justice, harmony, goodness, and so on. Self-actualizing people are more likely to have peak experiences. In other words, these \"peak experiences\" or states of flow are the reflections of the realization of one's human potential and represent the height of personality development.<ref>{{cite book|last=Schacter|first=Daniel|title=Psychology Second Edition|year=2009|page=487}}</ref>\n\nIn later writings Maslow moved to a more inclusive model that allowed for, in addition to intense peak experiences, longer-lasting periods of serene Being-cognition that he termed [[Peak experience#Plateau experience|''plateau experiences'']].<ref>Krippner, Stanley (1972). \n[https://www.academia.edu/27103672 The plateau experience: A. H. Maslow and others]. The Journal of Transpersonal Psychology, 4(2), 107\u2013120.</ref><ref>Gruel, Nicole (2015). \n[http://atpweb.org/jtparchive/trps-47-15-01-44.pdf The plateau experience: an exploration of its origins, characteristics, and potential]. ''The Journal of Transpersonal Psychology'', 47(1), 44\u221263.</ref> He borrowed this term from the Indian scientist and yoga praticioner, U. A. Asrani, with whom he corresponded.<ref>Gruel (2015), p. 50.</ref>\n\n===B-values===\nIn studying accounts of peak experiences, Maslow identified a manner of thought he called \"Being-cognition\" (or \"B-cognition\"), which is holistic and accepting, as opposed to the evaluative \"Deficiency-cognition\" (or \"D-cognition\"), and values he called \"Being-values\".<ref>{{cite book|last=Maslow|first=Abraham|title=The Farther Reaches of Human Nature|year=1993|publisher=Arkana|isbn=978-0140194708|page=128}}</ref> He listed the B-values as:\n* Truth (honesty; reality; nakedness; simplicity; richness; oughtness; beauty; pure, clean and unadulterated; completeness; essentiality).\n* Goodness (rightness; desirability; oughtness; justice; benevolence; honesty);\n* Beauty (rightness; form; aliveness; simplicity; richness; wholeness; perfection; completion; uniqueness; honesty);\n* Wholeness (unity; integration; tendency to one-ness; interconnectedness; simplicity; organization; structure; dichotomy-transcendence; order);\n* Aliveness (process; non-deadness; spontaneity; self-regulation; full-functioning);\n* Uniqueness (idiosyncrasy; individuality; non-comparability; novelty);\n* Perfection (necessity; just-right-ness; just-so-ness; inevitability; suitability; justice; completeness; \"oughtness\");\n* Completion (ending; finality; justice; \"it's finished\"; fulfillment; finis and telos; destiny; fate);\n* Justice (fairness; orderliness; lawfulness; \"oughtness\");\n* Simplicity (honesty; nakedness; essentiality; abstract, essential, skeletal structure);\n* Richness (differentiation, complexity; intricacy);\n* Effortlessness (ease; lack of strain, striving or difficulty; grace; perfect, beautiful functioning);\n* Playfulness (fun; joy; amusement; gaiety; humor; exuberance; effortlessness);\n* Self-sufficiency (autonomy; independence; not-needing-other-than-itself-in-order-to-be-itself; self-determining; environment-transcendence; separateness; living by its own laws).\n\n===Hierarchy of needs===\n[[File:Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs.svg|thumb|right|450px|An interpretation of Maslow's hierarchy of needs, represented as a pyramid, with the more basic needs at the bottom<ref name=\"abraham-maslow\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.abraham-maslow.com/m_motivation/Hierarchy_of_Needs.asp |title=Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs |access-date=2011-09-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907194523/http://www.abraham-maslow.com/m_motivation/Hierarchy_of_Needs.asp |archive-date=2011-09-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>]]\n{{main|Maslow's hierarchy of needs}}\nMaslow described human needs as ordered in a prepotent hierarchy\u2014a pressing need would need to be mostly satisfied before someone would give their attention to the next highest need. None of his published works included a visual representation of the hierarchy. The pyramidal diagram illustrating the Maslow needs hierarchy may have been created by a psychology textbook publisher as an illustrative device. This now iconic pyramid frequently depicts the spectrum of human needs, both physical and psychological, as accompaniment to articles describing Maslow's needs theory and may give the impression that the Hierarchy of Needs is a fixed and rigid sequence of progression. Yet, starting with the first publication of his theory in 1943, Maslow described human needs as being relatively fluid\u2014with many needs being present in a person simultaneously.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Maslow | first1 = A. H. | title = A theory of human motivation | doi = 10.1037/h0054346 | journal = Psychological Review | volume = 50 | issue = 4 | pages = 370\u2013396 | year = 1943 | pmid =  | pmc = | citeseerx = 10.1.1.334.7586 }}</ref>\n\nThe hierarchy of human needs model suggests that human needs will only be fulfilled one level at a time.<ref>Business Volume 1</ref>\n\nAccording to Maslow's theory, when a human being ascends the levels of the hierarchy having fulfilled the needs in the hierarchy, one may eventually achieve self-actualization. Late in life, Maslow came to conclude that self-actualization was not an automatic outcome of satisfying the other human needs <ref>Frick, W. B. (1989). Interview with Dr. Abraham Maslow. In Humanistic psychology: Conversations with Abraham Maslow, Gardner Murphy, Carl Rogers (pp. 19-50). Bristol, IN: Wyndham Hall Press. (Original work published 1971)</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Maslow | first1 = A. H. | title = A Theory of Metamotivation : The Biological Rooting of the Value-Life | doi = 10.1177/002216786700700201 | journal = Journal of Humanistic Psychology | volume = 7 | issue = 2 | pages = 93\u2013126 | year = 1967 | pmid =  | pmc = }}</ref>\n\nHuman needs as identified by Maslow:\n\n* At the bottom of the hierarchy are the \"Basic needs or Physiological needs\" of a human being: food, water, sleep, sex, homeostasis, and excretion. \n* The next level is \"Safety Needs: Security, Order, and Stability\". These two steps are important to the physical survival of the person. Once individuals have basic nutrition, shelter and safety, they attempt to accomplish more.\n* The third level of need is \"Love and Belonging\", which are psychological needs; when individuals have taken care of themselves physically, they are ready to share themselves with others, such as with family and friends.\n* The fourth level is achieved when individuals feel comfortable with what they have accomplished. This is the \"Esteem\" level, the need to be competent and recognized, such as through status and level of success.\n* Then there is the \"Cognitive\" level, where individuals intellectually stimulate themselves and explore.\n* After that is the \"Aesthetic\" level, which is the need for harmony, order and beauty.<ref>Carlson, N.R., et al. (2007). Psychology: The Science of Behaviour \u2013 4th Canadian ed. Toronto, ON: Pearson Education Canada.</ref>\n* At the top of the pyramid, \"Need for Self-actualization\" occurs when individuals reach a state of harmony and understanding because they are engaged in achieving their full potential.<ref>The Developing Person through the Life Span, (1983) pg. 44</ref> Once a person has reached the self-actualization state they focus on themselves and try to build their own image. They may look at this in terms of feelings such as self-confidence or by accomplishing a set goal.<ref name=\"Boeree\"/>\n\nThe first four levels are known as ''Deficit needs'' or ''D-needs''. This means that if you do not have enough of one of those four needs, you will have the feeling that you need to get it. But when you do get them, then you feel content. These needs alone are not motivating.<ref name=\"Boeree\"/>\n\nMaslow wrote that there are certain conditions that must be fulfilled in order for the basic needs to be satisfied. For example, freedom of speech, freedom to express oneself, and freedom to seek new information<ref>A Theory of Human Motivation</ref> are a few of the prerequisites. Any blockages of these freedoms could prevent the satisfaction of the basic needs.\n\nMaslow's Hierarchy is used in higher education for advising students and student retention<ref>Brookman, David M. \"Maslow's Hierarchy and Student Retention\". NACADA Journal, v9 n1 p69-74. Spring 1989.</ref> as well as a key concept in student development.<ref>Villa, R., Thousand, J., Stainback, W. & Stainback, S. [http://www.normemma.com/articles/armaslow.htm \"Restructuring for Caring & Effective Education\"].  Baltimore: Paul Brookes, 1992. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106011155/http://www.normemma.com/articles/armaslow.htm |date=November 6, 2012 }}</ref> Maslow's Hierarchy has been subject to internet memes over the past few years, specifically looking at the modern integration of technology in our lives and humorously suggesting that Wi-Fi was among the most basic of human needs.<ref name=Akufu>{{cite web|title=Maslow's Updated Hierarchy of Needs|url=http://weknowmemes.com/2013/08/maslows-hierarchy-of-needs-updated/|date=2013-08-20}}</ref>\n\n===Self-actualization===\n\nMaslow defined [[Self-actualization]] as achieving the fullest use of one's talents and interests\u2014the need \"to become everything that one is capable of becoming.\"<ref>Michael R. Hagerty, \"Testing Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs: National Quality-of-Life Across Time,\" Social Indicators Research 46(xx), 1999, 250.</ref>  As implied by its name, self-actualization is highly individualistic and reflects Maslow's premise that the self is \"sovereign and inviolable\" and entitled to \"his or her own tastes, opinions, values, etc.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Aron | first1 = Adrianne | year = 1977 | title = Maslow's Other Child | url = | journal = Journal of Humanistic Psychology | volume = 17 | issue = 2| page = 13 }}</ref>  Indeed, some have characterized self-actualization as \"healthy narcissism.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pauchant | first1 = Thierry | last2 = Dumas | first2 = Collette A. | year = 1991 | title = Abraham Maslow and Heinz Kohut: A Comparison | url = | journal = Journal of Humanistic Psychology | volume = 31 | issue = 2| page = 58 | doi = 10.1177/0022167891312005 }}</ref>\n\n===Qualities of self-actualizing people===\nHe realized that all the individuals he studied had similar personality traits. All were \"reality centered,\" able to differentiate what was fraudulent from what was genuine. They were also \"problem centered,\" meaning that they treated life's difficulties as problems that demanded solutions. These individuals also were comfortable being alone and had healthy personal relationships. They had only a few close friends and family rather than a large number of shallow relationships.<ref name=\"ship\">{{cite web|url=http://webspace.ship.edu/cgboer/maslow.html|title=ABRAHAM MASLOW|author=C. George Boeree|accessdate=2009-10-08| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091024142938/http://webspace.ship.edu/cgboer/maslow.html| archivedate= 24 October 2009| url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nSelf-actualizing people tend to focus on problems outside themselves; have a clear sense of what is true and what is false; are spontaneous and creative; and are not bound too strictly by social conventions.\n\nMaslow noticed that self-actualized individuals had a better insight of reality, deeply accepted themselves, others and the world, and also had faced many problems and were known to be impulsive people. These self-actualized individuals were very independent and private when it came to their environment and culture, especially their very own individual development on \"potentialities and inner resources\".<ref>{{cite journal |author=Richard L. Schott |year=1992 |title=Abraham Maslow, humanistic psychology, and organization leadership: a Jungian perspective |journal=[[Journal of Humanistic Psychology]] |volume=32 |pages=106\u2013120 |doi=10.1177/0022167892321008}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Maslow, self-actualizing people share the following qualities:\n* Truth: honest, reality, beauty, pure, clean and unadulterated completeness\n* Goodness: rightness, desirability, uprightness, benevolence, honesty\n* Beauty: rightness, form, aliveness, simplicity, richness, wholeness, perfection, completion,\n* Wholeness: unity, integration, tendency to oneness, interconnectedness, simplicity, organization, structure, order, not dissociated, synergy\n* Dichotomy: transcendence, acceptance, resolution, integration, polarities, opposites, contradictions\n* Aliveness: process, not-deadness, spontaneity, self-regulation, full-functioning\n* Uniqueness: idiosyncrasy, individuality, non comparability, novelty\n* Perfection: nothing superfluous, nothing lacking, everything in its right place, just-rightness, suitability, justice\n* Necessity: inevitability: it must be just that way, not changed in any slightest way\n* Completion: ending, justice, fulfillment\n* Justice: fairness, suitability,  disinterestedness, non partiality,\n* Order: lawfulness, rightness, perfectly arranged\n* Simplicity: nakedness, abstract, essential skeletal, bluntness\n* Richness: differentiation, complexity, intricacy, totality\n* Effortlessness: ease; lack of strain, striving, or difficulty\n* Playfulness: fun, joy, amusement\n* Self-sufficiency: autonomy, independence, self-determining.<ref name=\"Metaneeds\">{{cite web|url=http://webspace.ship.edu/cgboer/maslow.html |title=Metaneeds and metapathologies |accessdate=2010-04-12}}</ref>\n\nMaslow based his theory partially on his own assumptions about human potential and partially on his case studies of historical figures whom he believed to be self-actualized, including [[Albert Einstein]] and [[Henry David Thoreau]].<ref>Carlson, N. R. (19992000). Memory. Psychology: the science of behaviour (Canandian ed., p. 461). Scarborough, Ont.: Allyn and Bacon Canada.</ref> Consequently, Maslow argued, the way in which essential needs are fulfilled is just as important as the needs themselves. Together, these define the human experience. To the extent a person finds cooperative social fulfillment, he establishes meaningful relationships with other people and the larger world. In other words, he  establishes meaningful connections to an external reality\u2014an essential component of self-actualization. In contrast, to the extent that vital needs find selfish and competitive fulfillment, a person acquires hostile emotions and limited external relationships\u2014his awareness remains internal and limited.\n\n===Metamotivation===\nMaslow used the term [[metamotivation]] to describe self-actualized people who are driven by innate forces beyond their basic needs, so that they may explore and reach their full human potential.<ref>[[#Goble|Goble (1970)]]</ref>\n\n===Methodology===\nMaslow based his study on the writings of other psychologists, [[Albert Einstein]] and people he knew who [he felt] clearly met the standard of self-actualization.<ref>{{cite web|author=McLeod, S. A|year=2007|title= Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs|url=http://www.simplypsychology.org/maslow.html|publisher=Simplypsychology.org|accessdate=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nMaslow used Einstein's writings and accomplishments to exemplify the characteristics of the self-actualized person. But [[Ruth Benedict]] and [[Max Wertheimer]] were also Maslow's models of self-actualization.  In this case, from a scientific perspective there are numerous problems with this particular approach.  First, it could be argued that biographical analysis as a method is extremely subjective as it is based entirely on the opinion of the researcher.  Personal opinion is always prone to bias, which reduces the validity of any data obtained.  Therefore, Maslow's operational definition of Self-actualization must not be blindly accepted as scientific fact.<ref>{{cite web|author=McLeod, S. A|year=2007|title= Maslow's Hierarchy of Needs|url=http://www.simplypsychology.org/maslow.html|publisher=Simplypsychology.org|accessdate=2012-10-21}}</ref>\n\n===Transpersonal psychology===\nDuring the 1960s Maslow founded with Stanislav Grof, Viktor Frankl, James Fadiman, Anthony Sutich, Miles Vich and Michael Murphy, the school of [[transpersonal psychology]]. Maslow had concluded that humanistic psychology was incapable of explaining all aspects of human experience. He identified various mystical, ecstatic, or spiritual states known as \"[[peak experiences]]\" as experiences beyond self-actualization. Maslow called these experiences \"a fourth force in psychology\", which he named transpersonal psychology. Transpersonal psychology was concerned with the \"empirical, scientific study of, and responsible implementation of the finding relevant to, becoming, mystical, ecstatic, and spiritual states\" (Olson & Hergenhahn, 2011).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nMaslow published in 1962 a collection of papers on this theme, which developed into his 1968 book ''Toward a Psychology of Being''.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|author1=Matthew H. Olson|author2=B. R. Hergenhahn|title=An Introduction to Theories of Personality|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ISJ6QgAACAAJ|year=2011|publisher=Prentice Hall/Pearson|isbn=978-0-205-79878-0}}</ref><ref name=\"Maslow2013\">{{cite book|author=Abraham H. Maslow|title=Toward a Psychology of Being|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jcKbDAAAQBAJ|date=18 July 2013|orig-year=first published 1968|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-62793-274-5}}</ref> In this book Maslow stresses the importance of transpersonal psychology to human beings, writing: \"without the transpersonal, we get sick, violent, and nihilistic, or else hopeless and apathetic\" (Olson & Hergenhahn, 2011).<ref name=\":0\" /> Human beings, he came to believe, need something bigger than themselves that they are connected to in a naturalistic sense, but not in a religious sense: Maslow himself was an [[Atheism|atheist]]<ref name=\"Hamer2005\">{{cite book|author=Dean H. Hamer|title=The God Gene: How Faith Is Hardwired into Our Genes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKRphq7s7x0C&pg=PA19|date=27 September 2005|publisher=Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-307-27693-3|pages=19\u2013}}</ref> and found it difficult to accept religious experience as valid unless placed in a [[Positivism|positivistic]] framework.<ref name=\"Hoffman, E. 1999\">{{cite book|author=Edward Hoffman|title=The Right to Be Human: A Biography of Abraham Maslow|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=USSePwAACAAJ|date=1 March 1994|publisher=Four Worlds Press|isbn=978-0-9637902-3-1}}</ref> In fact, Maslow's position on God and religion was quite complex. While he rejected organized religion and its beliefs, he wrote extensively on the human being's need for the sacred and spoke of God in more philosophical terms, as beauty, truth and goodness, or as a force or a principle.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.awaken.com/2013/01/abraham-maslow-and-spirituality/|title=Abraham Maslow and Spirituality {{!}} Awaken|website=www.awaken.com|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oaks.nvg.org/maslow-rvl.html|title=Abraham Maslow on Religion, Values of Self-actualisers, and Peak Experiences \u2013 The Gold Scales|website=oaks.nvg.org|access-date=2019-03-15}}</ref>\n\nAwareness of transpersonal psychology became widespread within psychology, and the ''Journal of Transpersonal Psychology'' was founded in 1969, a year after Abraham Maslow became the president of the American Psychological Association. In the United States, transpersonal psychology encouraged recognition for [[non-western]] psychologies, philosophies, and religions, and promoted understanding of \"higher states of consciousness\", for instance through intense [[meditation]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thepositiveencourager.global/abraham-maslows-approach-to-doing-positive-work/|title=M is for Abraham Maslow: A Founder of Humanistic Psychology|date=2014-12-19|newspaper=The Positive Encourager|access-date=2016-12-13}}</ref> Transpersonal psychology has been applied in many areas, including [[transpersonal business studies]].\n\n===Positive psychology===\nMaslow called his work [[positive psychology]].<ref>''Two Thoughts on Abraham Maslow'' by David L Rennie</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Two Thoughts on Abraham Maslow - David Rennie | publisher=Journal of Humanistic Psychology | date= }}</ref> His work has influenced since 1968 the development of [[Positive Psychotherapy]], a transcultural, humanistic based psychodynamic psychotherapy method used in mental health and psychosomatic treatment founded by [[Nossrat Peseschkian]].<ref>''Positive Psychotherapie'' by Nossrat Peseschkian. Fischer: 1977. ''Positive Psychotherapy'' by Nossrat Peseschkian. Springer: 1987.</ref> Since 1999 Maslows work enjoyed a revival of interest and influence among leaders of the [[positive psychology]] movement such as [[Martin Seligman]]. This movement focuses only on a higher human nature.<ref>''Character Strengths and Virtues: A Handbook and Classification'' by Christopher Peterson, Martin E. P. Seligman. Oxford University Press: 2004 {{ISBN|0-19-516701-5}} pg 62</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QqPiF1C7cy4C&pg=PA62&lpg=PA62&dq=maslow+seligmann#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Character Strengths and Virtues: A Handbook and Classification - Christopher Peterson, Martin E. P. Seligman - Google Books |accessdate=2012-10-21|isbn=9780195167016 |year=2004 |last1=Peterson |first1=Christopher |last2=Seligman |first2=Martin E. P. |last3=Fox Leadership Professor Of Psychology Martin e p Seligman |first3=Ph.D }}</ref>\nPositive psychology spends its research looking at the positive side of things and how they go right rather than the pessimistic side.<ref>Gilbert, D. (2006). Stumbling on happiness. Toronto, Ontario: Random House.</ref>\n\n=== Psychology of science ===\nIn 1966, Maslow published a pioneering work in the psychology of science ''The Psychology of Science: A Reconnaissance'', the first book ever actually titled \u2018psychology of science\u2019. In this book Maslow proposed a model of \u2018characterologically relative\u2019 science, which he characterized as an ardent opposition to the \u2018\u2018historically, philosophically, sociologically and psychologically na\u0131ve\u2019\u2019 positivistic reluctance to see science \u2018\u2018relative to time, place, and local culture\u2019\u2019.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Psychology of Science: A Reconnaissance|last=Maslow|first=Abraham|publisher=Gateway Editions|year=1969|isbn=|location=South Bend, Indiana|pages=1|via=}}</ref> As Maslow acknowledged, the book was greatly inspired by Thomas Kuhn's ''The Structure of Scientific Revolutions'' (1962), and it offers a psychological reading of Kuhn's famous distinction between \"normal\" and \"revolutionary\" science in the context of his own distinction between \"safety\" and \"growth\" science, put forward as part of a larger program for the psychology of science, outlined already in his 1954 ''magnum opus'' ''Motivation and Personality''. Not only that Maslow offered a psychological reading of Kuhn's categories of \"normal\" and \"revolutionary\" science as an aftermath of Kuhn's ''Structure'', but he also offered a strikingly similar dichotomous structure of science 16 years before the first edition of ''Structure'', in his nowadays little known 1946 paper \"Means-Centering Versus Problem-Centering in Science\" published in the journal ''Philosophy of Science''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ko\u017enjak|first=Boris|date=2017|title=Kuhn Meets Maslow: The Psychology Behind Scientific Revolutions|journal=Journal for General Philosophy of Science|volume=48|issue=2|pages=257\u2013287|doi=10.1007/s10838-016-9352-x}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maslow|first=Abraham|date=1946|title=Problem-centering vs. means-centering in science|journal=Philosophy of Science|volume=13 |issue=4 |pages=326\u2013331 |doi=10.1086/286907|jstor=185213}}</ref>\n\n===Maslow's hammer===\nAbraham Maslow is also known for [[Maslow's hammer]], popularly phrased as \"[[wikt:if all you have is a hammer, everything looks like a nail|if all you have is a hammer, everything looks like a nail]]\"  from his book ''The Psychology of Science'', published in 1966.<ref name=maslow66>\n{{cite book\n | title = The Psychology of Science\n | author = Abraham H. Maslow\n | year = 1966\n | isbn =9780976040231| page = 15\n | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=3_40fK8PW6QC&printsec=frontcover#PPT7,M1\n | accessdate = 2015-12-20\n}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nMaslow's ideas have been criticized for their lack of scientific rigor. He was criticized as too soft scientifically by American empiricists.<ref name=\"Hoffman, E. 1999\"/> In 2006, author and former philosophy professor [[Christina Hoff Sommers]] and practicing psychiatrist [[Sally Satel]] asserted that, due to lack of empirical support, Maslow's ideas have fallen out of fashion and are \"no longer taken seriously in the world of academic psychology.\"<ref>[[#Sommers|Sommers & Satel (2006)]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=sVT_i83KAhMC&dq=one+nation+under+therapy&printsec=frontcover&source=bn&hl=en&ei=2jrjS9GiKJPssQPe-JW6DQ&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=4&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=maslow&f=false p. 74 & passim in chapter 2]</ref>\nPositive psychology spends much of its research looking for how things go right rather than the more pessimistic view point, how things go wrong.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Peterson|first= C. |year=2009|title= Positive psychology. |journal = Reclaiming Children and Youth|volume= 18|issue=2|pages= 3\u20137}}</ref>\nFurthermore, the Hierarchy of Needs has been accused of having a cultural bias\u2014mainly reflecting Western values and ideologies. From the perspective of many cultural psychologists, this concept is considered relative to each culture and society and cannot be universally applied.<ref>Keith E Rice,[http://www.integratedsociopsychology.net/hierearchy_of_needs.html \"Hierarchy of Needs\"], ''Integrated Sociopsychology'', 9/12/12 {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212143440/http://www.integratedsociopsychology.net/hierearchy_of_needs.html |date=February 12, 2015 }}</ref> However, according to the University of Illinois researchers Ed Diener and Louis Tay,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Diener|first=Ed|last2=Tay|first2=Louis|date=2011|title=Needs and subjective well-being around the world|url=|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume=101 |issue=2|pages=354\u2013365|doi=10.1037/a0023779|pmid=21688922|access-date=}}</ref> who put Maslow's ideas to the test with data collected from 60,865 participants in 123 countries around the world over the period of five years (2005-2010), Maslow was essentially right in that there are universal human needs regardless of cultural differences, although the authors claim to have found certain departures from the order of their fulfillment Maslow described. In particular, while they found&mdash;clearly in accordance with Maslow&mdash;that people tend to achieve basic and safety needs before other needs, as well as that other \"higher needs\" tend to be fulfilled in a certain order, the order in which they are fulfilled apparently does not strongly influence their subjective well-being (SWB). As put by the authors of the study, humans thus\n\n{{Quote|text=can derive 'happiness' from simultaneously working on a number of needs regardless of the fulfillment of other needs. This might be why people in impoverished nations, with only modest control over whether their basic needs are fulfilled, can nevertheless find a measure of well-being through social relationships and other psychological needs over which they have more control.|sign=|source=Diener & Tay (2011), p. 364}}\n\nMaslow, however, would not be surprised by these findings, since he clearly and repeatedly emphasized that the need hierarchy is not a rigid fixed order as it is often presented:\n\n{{Quote|text=We have spoken so far as if this hierarchy were a fixed order, but actually it is not nearly so rigid as we may have implied. It is true that most of the people with whom we have worked have seemed to have these basic needs in about the order that has been indicated. However, there have been a number of exceptions.|sign=|source=Maslow, 'Motivation and Personality' (1970), p. 51}}\n\nMaslow also regarded that the relationship between different human needs and behaviour, being in fact often motivated simultaneously by multiple needs, is not a one-to-one correspondence, i.e., that \"these needs must be understood not to be exclusive or single determiners of certain kinds of behavior\".<ref>{{Cite book|title=Motivation and Personalty|last=Maslow|first=Abraham|year=1970|isbn=|location=|pages=55|via=}}</ref>\n\nMaslow's concept of self-actualizing people was united with Piaget's developmental theory to the process of initiation in 1993.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.academia.edu/663726|title=Oliver Kress - A new approach to cognitive development: ontogenesis and the process of initiation|author=Oliver Kress|accessdate=2015-12-20}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nLater in life, Maslow was concerned with questions such as, \"Why don't more people self-actualize if their basic needs are met?\nHow can we humanistically understand the problem of evil?\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rennie, David |year=2008 |title=Two thoughts on Abraham Maslow|journal= Journal of Humanistic Psychology|volume= 48|issue=4|pages=445\u2013448|doi=10.1177/0022167808320537}}</ref>\n\nIn the spring of 1961, Maslow and Tony Sutich founded the ''Journal of Humanistic Psychology'', with Miles Vich as editor until 1971.<ref name=\"Greening\">{{cite journal|author=Greening, Tom |year=2008 |title=Abraham Maslow: A Brief Reminiscence|journal= Journal of Humanistic Psychology|volume=48|issue=4 |pages=443\u2013444 |doi=10.1177/0022167808320533 }}</ref> The journal printed its first issue in early 1961 and continues to publish academic papers.<ref name=\"Greening\"/>\n\nMaslow attended the Association for Humanistic Psychology's founding meeting in 1963 where he declined nomination as its president, arguing that the new organization should develop an intellectual movement without a leader which resulted in useful strategy during the field's early years.<ref>Abraham Maslow: A Brief Reminiscence\nJournal of Humanistic Psychology (October 2008), 48 (4), pg. 443-444 \nTom Greening</ref>\n\nIn 1967, Maslow was named [[Humanist of the Year]] by the [[American Humanist Association]].<ref name=AHA>{{cite web|title=Humanists of the Year|url=http://americanhumanist.org/AHA/Humanists_of_the_Year|work=American Humanist Association|accessdate=14 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Writings==\n* \"[http://psychclassics.yorku.ca/Maslow/motivation.htm A Theory of Human Motivation]\" (originally published in ''Psychological Review'', 1943, Vol. 50 #4, pp.&nbsp;370\u2013396).\n* ''[[Motivation and Personality]]'' (1st edition: 1954, 2nd edition: 1970, 3rd edition 1987)\n* ''[[Religions, Values, and Peak Experiences]]'', Columbus, Ohio: [[Ohio State University Press]], 1964.\n* ''[[Eupsychian Management]]'', 1965; republished as ''[[Maslow on Management]]'', 1998\n* ''The Psychology of Science: A Reconnaissance'', New York: [[Harper & Row]], 1966; Chapel Hill: Maurice Bassett, 2002.\n* ''Toward a Psychology of Being'', (1st edition, 1962; 2nd edition, 1968)\n* ''The Farther Reaches of Human Nature'', 1971\n* ''Future Visions: The Unpublished Papers of Abraham Maslow'' by E. L. Hoffman (editor) 1996\n* ''Personality and Growth: A Humanistic Psychologist in the Classroom'', Anna Maria, FL: Maurice Bassett, 2019.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Psychology}}\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Clayton Alderfer]]\n* [[Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi]]\n* [[Frederick Herzberg]]\n* [[Human Potential Movement]]\n* [[Law of the instrument]]\n* [[Manfred Max-Neef]]\n* [[Rollo May]]\n* [[Organismic theory]]\n* [[Organizational behavior]]\n* [[Positive Disintegration]]\n* [[Post-materialism]]\n* [[Reverence (emotion)|Reverence]]\n* [[Self-esteem]]\n* [[Victor Vroom]]\n* [[Erich Fromm]]\n* [[Humanistic psychology]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Developing Person through the Life Span |last=Berger |first=Kathleen Stassen |year=1983 |ref=Berger}}\n* {{cite book |title=The Third Force: The Psychology of Abraham Maslow |last=Goble |first=F. |publisher=Maurice Bassett Publishing |year=1970 |location=Richmond, CA |ref=Goble}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Goud, N  |year=2008 |title=Abraham maslow: A personal statement. |journal=Journal of Humanistic Psychology |volume=48 |issue=4 |pages=448\u2013451 |doi=10.1177/0022167808320535|first1=N. }}\n* {{cite book |title=The Right to be Human: A Biography of Abraham Maslow |url=https://archive.org/details/righttobehuman00edwa |url-access=registration |last=Hoffman |first=Edward |publisher=St. Martin's Press |year=1988 |location=New York |ref=Hoffman}}\n* {{Citation | last =Hoffman | first =E. | title =Abraham Maslow: A Brief Reminiscence. In: Journal of Humanistic Psychology Fall 2008 vol. 48 no. 4 443-444  | year =1999 | place =New York | publisher =McGraw-Hill}}\n* {{cite journal |last=Rennie  | first =David  |year=2008 |title=Two Thoughts on Abraham Maslow. | journal =Journal of Humanistic Psychology  | volume =48  | issue =4  | pages =445\u2013448  |doi=10.1177/0022167808320537}}\n* {{cite book |title=One Nation Under Therapy: How the Helping Culture is Eroding Self-reliance |last2=Satel |first2=Sally |publisher=MacMillan |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-312-30444-7 |ref=Sommers|last1=Sommers |first1=Christina Hoff }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Library resources box|by=yes|onlinebooks=no|about=yes|wikititle=Abraham Maslow}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Cooke | first1 = B | last2 = Mills | first2 = A | last3 = Kelley | first3 = E | year = 2005 | title = Situating Maslow in Cold War America | url = | journal = Group and Organization Management | volume = 30 | issue = 2| pages = 129\u2013152 | doi=10.1177/1059601104273062}}\n* DeCarvalho, Roy Jose (1991) ''The Founders of Humanistic Psychology''. Praeger Publishers\n* Grogan, Jessica (2012) ''Encountering America: Humanistic Psychology, Sixties Culture, and the Shaping of the Modern Self''. Harper Perennial \n* Hoffman, Edward (1999) ''The Right to Be Human''. McGraw-Hill  {{ISBN|0-07-134267-2}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Wahba | first1 = M.A. | last2 = Bridwell | first2 = L. G. | year = 1976 | title = Maslow Reconsidered: A Review of Research on the Need Hierarchy Theory | url = | journal = Organizational Behavior and Human Performance | volume = 15 | issue = 2| pages = 212\u2013240 | doi=10.1016/0030-5073(76)90038-6}}\n* Wilson, Colin (1972) ''New Pathways in Psychology: Maslow and the post-Freudian revolution''. London: Victor Gollancz ({{ISBN|0-575-01355-9}})\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|Abraham Maslow}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051203221954/http://www.maslow.org/sub/m_bib.htm Comprehensive bibliography of Maslow's works]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071022173753/http://faculty.vassar.edu/lowry/maslow1.html \"Maslow's Vision of Human Nature\"] adapted from the Editor's Introduction to ''Toward a Psychology of Being'' (3rd ed.)\n* [http://www.panarchy.org/maslow/being.1955.html Excerpts from ''Toward a Psychology of Being'', 2nd ed.]\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Abraham Harold Maslow}}\n* {{Librivox author |id=3653}}\n* [http://www.abrahammaslow.com/podcasts.html Abraham Maslow Audio Collection]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sfmo04EZP3o \"Being Abraham Maslow\". Rare documentary about Abraham Maslow in a conversation with Warren Bennis of the University of Cincinnati from 1968.]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151220204237/http://www.muskingum.edu/~psych/psycweb/history/maslow.htm Psychology History-Abraham Maslow, Compiled by Michelle Emrich]\n\n{{APA Presidents}}\n{{Psychology}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maslow, Abraham}}\n[[Category:1908 births]]\n[[Category:1970 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century psychologists]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American humanists]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American psychologists]]\n[[Category:American psychology writers]]\n[[Category:Boys High School (Brooklyn) alumni]]\n[[Category:Brandeis University faculty]]\n[[Category:Brooklyn College faculty]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:History of mental health]]\n[[Category:Humanistic psychologists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American social scientists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish atheists]]\n[[Category:Motivation theorists]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from Menlo Park, California]]\n[[Category:Positive psychologists]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the American Psychological 